WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.279 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.279 --> 00:00:11.945 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA GARR: Hi.

00:00:11.945 --> 00:00:14.130 align:middle line:84%
I'm Lisa Garr, host of
"Gaiam Inspirations,"

00:00:14.130 --> 00:00:16.264 align:middle line:84%
and we're broadcasting
from the Sounds True Wake

00:00:16.264 --> 00:00:17.930 align:middle line:84%
Up Festival in the
beautiful Rockies

00:00:17.930 --> 00:00:20.330 align:middle line:84%
surrounding Estes
Park in Colorado.

00:00:20.330 --> 00:00:22.960 align:middle line:84%
So most of our greatest
joys and sorrows

00:00:22.960 --> 00:00:25.570 align:middle line:84%
happen with our
relationships with others.

00:00:25.570 --> 00:00:28.660 align:middle line:84%
Our days are basically a dance
between relating with others

00:00:28.660 --> 00:00:30.520 align:middle line:90%
and relating back to ourselves.

00:00:30.520 --> 00:00:32.534 align:middle line:84%
If this consumes
most of our day,

00:00:32.534 --> 00:00:34.200 align:middle line:84%
wouldn't it be great
if you could really

00:00:34.200 --> 00:00:38.360 align:middle line:84%
learn to guide your mind
to forgiveness and healing

00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:41.629 align:middle line:84%
and find a greater happiness
and connection with others?

00:00:41.629 --> 00:00:43.420 align:middle line:84%
Well, that's what we're
talking about today

00:00:43.420 --> 00:00:45.580 align:middle line:84%
with neuropsychologist
Rick Hansen.

00:00:45.580 --> 00:00:49.530 align:middle line:84%
He teaches how brain science,
practical psychology,

00:00:49.530 --> 00:00:51.960 align:middle line:84%
and Buddhist
meditation practices

00:00:51.960 --> 00:00:55.460 align:middle line:84%
are able to help us achieve
greater intimacy with ourselves

00:00:55.460 --> 00:00:56.790 align:middle line:90%
and in our relationships.

00:00:56.790 --> 00:00:57.444 align:middle line:90%
Welcome.

00:00:57.444 --> 00:00:59.610 align:middle line:84%
>>RICK HANSON: It's great
to be here, Lisa-- really.

00:00:59.610 --> 00:01:01.651 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: This is going to
be so fun, because we're

00:01:01.651 --> 00:01:05.168 align:middle line:84%
going to just connect with
our brain chemistry today.

00:01:05.168 --> 00:01:05.980 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Oh!

00:01:05.980 --> 00:01:07.910 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So let's talk
about relationships.

00:01:07.910 --> 00:01:11.200 align:middle line:84%
So, every single day, we're
relating with others-- people

00:01:11.200 --> 00:01:16.730 align:middle line:84%
in lines and cars when we
drive, with our loved ones.

00:01:16.730 --> 00:01:21.220 align:middle line:84%
How do you not carry the baggage
over into the relationships

00:01:21.220 --> 00:01:21.840 align:middle line:90%
to affect?

00:01:21.840 --> 00:01:25.427 align:middle line:84%
How do you start new every day,
I think is what I'm asking?

00:01:25.427 --> 00:01:26.010 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Wow.

00:01:26.010 --> 00:01:27.010 align:middle line:90%
That's a great question.

00:01:27.010 --> 00:01:29.990 align:middle line:84%
Well, I think for one, it's
natural to not start new.

00:01:29.990 --> 00:01:33.490 align:middle line:84%
In other words, we're designed
to learn from our experiences.

00:01:33.490 --> 00:01:36.665 align:middle line:84%
And it would be, in a way,
odd to wake up and roll

00:01:36.665 --> 00:01:38.744 align:middle line:84%
over and go, who
are you, anyway?

00:01:38.744 --> 00:01:39.285 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:01:39.285 --> 00:01:39.640 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Right?

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:41.390 align:middle line:84%
There would be a little
trouble with that.

00:01:41.390 --> 00:01:43.420 align:middle line:84%
So I think sometimes
people feel bad about still

00:01:43.420 --> 00:01:44.570 align:middle line:90%
being affected by things.

00:01:44.570 --> 00:01:46.866 align:middle line:84%
But it's natural to
be affected by things.

00:01:46.866 --> 00:01:48.990 align:middle line:84%
The Buddha had a nice
metaphor for that-- the first

00:01:48.990 --> 00:01:50.180 align:middle line:90%
and the second dart.

00:01:50.180 --> 00:01:52.900 align:middle line:84%
The first dart is what affects
us in the first place--

00:01:52.900 --> 00:01:54.180 align:middle line:90%
physically and emotionally.

00:01:54.180 --> 00:01:54.850 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:54.850 --> 00:01:56.433 align:middle line:84%
But then we had
second, third, fourth,

00:01:56.433 --> 00:01:58.130 align:middle line:84%
and fifth darts that
we throw ourselves.

00:01:58.130 --> 00:02:00.870 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes those second,
third, fourth, or fifth darts,

00:02:00.870 --> 00:02:03.220 align:middle line:84%
especially for people who
have done some inner work,

00:02:03.220 --> 00:02:06.430 align:middle line:84%
is that they feel bad
about feeling bad.

00:02:06.430 --> 00:02:09.770 align:middle line:84%
So step one is to let go of
that one as much as possible.

00:02:09.770 --> 00:02:11.900 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: We throw the darts
back or more darts get--

00:02:11.900 --> 00:02:12.210 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: At ourselves.

00:02:12.210 --> 00:02:12.620 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: At ourselves.

00:02:12.620 --> 00:02:12.730 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: We throw
them at ourselves.

00:02:12.730 --> 00:02:14.310 align:middle line:90%
We criticize ourselves.

00:02:14.310 --> 00:02:16.890 align:middle line:84%
Why am I still irritated with
my partner over that thing?

00:02:16.890 --> 00:02:19.370 align:middle line:84%
Oh, I must not have meditated
or done enough therapy,

00:02:19.370 --> 00:02:20.921 align:middle line:90%
or whatever enough.

00:02:20.921 --> 00:02:21.420 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:02:21.420 --> 00:02:22.610 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Can't I just let it go?

00:02:22.610 --> 00:02:23.235 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:02:23.235 --> 00:02:24.816 align:middle line:90%
Like step one-- hey, I am upset.

00:02:24.816 --> 00:02:26.190 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's
really important

00:02:26.190 --> 00:02:28.430 align:middle line:84%
to start with a kind of
kindness for yourself.

00:02:28.430 --> 00:02:30.850 align:middle line:84%
Because if you can't be
really kind to yourself,

00:02:30.850 --> 00:02:33.202 align:middle line:84%
it's hard to sustain
kindness for other people

00:02:33.202 --> 00:02:34.660 align:middle line:84%
because we start
feeling like we're

00:02:34.660 --> 00:02:36.665 align:middle line:84%
running on empty,
running on fumes.

00:02:36.665 --> 00:02:37.229 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:02:37.229 --> 00:02:39.020 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: So that would
be part one for me.

00:02:39.020 --> 00:02:42.020 align:middle line:84%
Part two for me is
to really appreciate

00:02:42.020 --> 00:02:44.520 align:middle line:90%
how good it feels to let go.

00:02:44.520 --> 00:02:46.750 align:middle line:90%
Make a tight fist.

00:02:46.750 --> 00:02:51.210 align:middle line:84%
Oh, 10 seconds-- I
just wanna let go.

00:02:51.210 --> 00:02:53.077 align:middle line:90%
And it feels so good to let go.

00:02:53.077 --> 00:02:54.410 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It starts to flow again.

00:02:54.410 --> 00:02:55.034 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:02:55.034 --> 00:02:58.540 align:middle line:84%
So to let go in relationships--
so valuing letting go,

00:02:58.540 --> 00:03:03.190 align:middle line:84%
realizing why it's good for
me to let go of my grievances

00:03:03.190 --> 00:03:04.340 align:middle line:90%
with you.

00:03:04.340 --> 00:03:07.270 align:middle line:84%
Now, third, I need to take
action if it's appropriate.

00:03:07.270 --> 00:03:09.940 align:middle line:84%
We need to talk about something
that's real, et cetera.

00:03:09.940 --> 00:03:14.030 align:middle line:84%
But if my mind is caught-- and I
call it the simulator-- looping

00:03:14.030 --> 00:03:17.250 align:middle line:84%
over that conversation,
rewriting that email,

00:03:17.250 --> 00:03:21.070 align:middle line:84%
wondering why others
didn't step in.

00:03:21.070 --> 00:03:22.950 align:middle line:84%
Because, as you know,
the famous saying--

00:03:22.950 --> 00:03:25.520 align:middle line:84%
neurons that fire
together wire together.

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:29.050 align:middle line:84%
Well, you are wiring that
negativity, that resentment,

00:03:29.050 --> 00:03:33.220 align:middle line:84%
that low self-esteem, that
case against other people,

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:35.490 align:middle line:84%
that mistrust of
life altogether--

00:03:35.490 --> 00:03:36.970 align:middle line:84%
you're wiring that
into your brain.

00:03:36.970 --> 00:03:38.720 align:middle line:84%
Plus, we have a
brain-- as you know--

00:03:38.720 --> 00:03:41.440 align:middle line:84%
that's very vulnerable
to over-learning

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:42.794 align:middle line:90%
from negative experiences.

00:03:42.794 --> 00:03:44.460 align:middle line:84%
That's the negativity
bias of the brain.

00:03:44.460 --> 00:03:48.090 align:middle line:84%
Then I say like, Velcro for
the bad, Teflon for the good.

00:03:48.090 --> 00:03:51.031 align:middle line:90%
So summing it up.

00:03:51.031 --> 00:03:53.060 align:middle line:84%
I want to, myself--
there's enough

00:03:53.060 --> 00:03:54.550 align:middle line:90%
suffering in life as it is.

00:03:54.550 --> 00:03:58.550 align:middle line:84%
I don't want to add excess
needless suffering, including

00:03:58.550 --> 00:04:00.370 align:middle line:84%
getting all cranky
about other people.

00:04:00.370 --> 00:04:02.850 align:middle line:84%
I want to move to letting
go as soon as possible

00:04:02.850 --> 00:04:06.080 align:middle line:84%
and try to find that
sweet spot between love

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:08.350 align:middle line:84%
and power, compassion
and assertiveness.

00:04:08.350 --> 00:04:10.000 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So you do
this consciously.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:10.800 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Very.

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:11.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I mean, yeah.

00:04:11.920 --> 00:04:12.040 align:middle line:90%
It does--

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:14.390 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: When I'm on my game,
which isn't all the time.

00:04:14.390 --> 00:04:16.444 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It takes a
conscious action, because,

00:04:16.444 --> 00:04:17.819 align:middle line:84%
as you just said--
and I want you

00:04:17.819 --> 00:04:19.510 align:middle line:90%
to expand this a little bit.

00:04:19.510 --> 00:04:22.490 align:middle line:84%
Why does the brain
hold on to negativity?

00:04:22.490 --> 00:04:26.234 align:middle line:84%
Why is it so much more impactful
on the brain than positivity?

00:04:26.234 --> 00:04:26.900 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Right.

00:04:26.900 --> 00:04:27.401 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Why?

00:04:27.401 --> 00:04:29.025 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Well, this
is what scientists

00:04:29.025 --> 00:04:30.730 align:middle line:84%
call the negativity
bias of the brain--

00:04:30.730 --> 00:04:31.980 align:middle line:90%
tons of studies about it.

00:04:31.980 --> 00:04:34.880 align:middle line:84%
The bottom line is that
as our ancestors evolved

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:37.370 align:middle line:84%
and the nervous system
has been evolving

00:04:37.370 --> 00:04:41.490 align:middle line:84%
for 600 million years-- I
think of each one of us having

00:04:41.490 --> 00:04:45.370 align:middle line:84%
inside a little lizard, mouse,
and monkey loosely associated

00:04:45.370 --> 00:04:48.300 align:middle line:84%
with the brain stem
subcortex and primate stages

00:04:48.300 --> 00:04:49.350 align:middle line:90%
of evolution.

00:04:49.350 --> 00:04:53.190 align:middle line:84%
And those little critters were
living in tough conditions.

00:04:53.190 --> 00:04:56.200 align:middle line:84%
So they had to both get
carrots and avoid sticks--

00:04:56.200 --> 00:04:58.910 align:middle line:84%
carrots like food, mating
opportunities, et cetera;

00:04:58.910 --> 00:05:01.135 align:middle line:84%
sticks like predators,
natural hazards--

00:05:01.135 --> 00:05:01.760 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Danger.

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:02.380 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah, dangers.

00:05:02.380 --> 00:05:02.610 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:02.610 --> 00:05:04.550 align:middle line:84%
Both are important, but
here's the difference.

00:05:04.550 --> 00:05:06.660 align:middle line:84%
If you fail to get
a carrot today,

00:05:06.660 --> 00:05:08.800 align:middle line:84%
you'll have a chance
at a carrot tomorrow.

00:05:08.800 --> 00:05:11.734 align:middle line:84%
But if you fail to avoid
that stick today, whack.

00:05:11.734 --> 00:05:12.900 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: There's no tomorrow.

00:05:12.900 --> 00:05:14.110 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: No more
carrots forever.

00:05:14.110 --> 00:05:14.650 align:middle line:90%
Exactly.

00:05:14.650 --> 00:05:17.540 align:middle line:84%
So now we have a brain
that does four things.

00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:19.390 align:middle line:90%
One, it scans for bad news.

00:05:19.390 --> 00:05:21.450 align:middle line:90%
Two, it hyperfocuses on it.

00:05:21.450 --> 00:05:23.280 align:middle line:90%
Three, it overreacts to it.

00:05:23.280 --> 00:05:25.990 align:middle line:84%
For example, if you play
two sounds for people

00:05:25.990 --> 00:05:29.030 align:middle line:84%
inside an MRI, they're equally
loud, but one is pleasant,

00:05:29.030 --> 00:05:30.210 align:middle line:90%
one is unpleasant.

00:05:30.210 --> 00:05:31.020 align:middle line:90%
Wing!

00:05:31.020 --> 00:05:33.200 align:middle line:84%
The brain reacts more
to the unpleasant.

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:34.750 align:middle line:84%
And then, fourth,
the whole package

00:05:34.750 --> 00:05:37.310 align:middle line:84%
is fast-tracked into
emotional memory.

00:05:37.310 --> 00:05:39.310 align:middle line:90%
Once burned, twice shy.

00:05:39.310 --> 00:05:41.430 align:middle line:84%
So, for example, think
about a relationship.

00:05:41.430 --> 00:05:45.101 align:middle line:84%
10 things happen in a day, nine
are positive, one's negative.

00:05:45.101 --> 00:05:45.600 align:middle line:90%
Hmm.

00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:47.420 align:middle line:84%
What's the one you think
about when you go to sleep

00:05:47.420 --> 00:05:49.170 align:middle line:84%
or when you get up the
next morning, which

00:05:49.170 --> 00:05:50.623 align:middle line:90%
is where we started here.

00:05:50.623 --> 00:05:51.206 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:05:51.206 --> 00:05:52.705 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Relationships,
since we're

00:05:52.705 --> 00:05:57.000 align:middle line:84%
talking about that--
interactions in relationships.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.761 align:middle line:84%
Negative ones have much more
power than positive ones.

00:05:59.761 --> 00:06:01.760 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's why the
daily news is so popular,

00:06:01.760 --> 00:06:02.720 align:middle line:90%
or the nightly news.

00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:03.020 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:06:03.020 --> 00:06:03.520 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:06:03.520 --> 00:06:05.320 align:middle line:84%
If it bleeds, it
leads in journalism.

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:06.320 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, absolutely.

00:06:06.320 --> 00:06:07.090 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:06:07.090 --> 00:06:10.030 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So why is it sometimes
when we have a bad day,

00:06:10.030 --> 00:06:12.570 align:middle line:84%
we take it out on the
ones we love the most.

00:06:12.570 --> 00:06:14.487 align:middle line:90%
What is that?

00:06:14.487 --> 00:06:16.320 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: I think it's
for a lot of reasons.

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:18.610 align:middle line:84%
One, they're safer
to take it out on.

00:06:18.610 --> 00:06:21.325 align:middle line:84%
Because if you take it out on
your boss or the police officer

00:06:21.325 --> 00:06:24.210 align:middle line:84%
who pulled you over
for a ticket-- uh oh.

00:06:24.210 --> 00:06:25.460 align:middle line:90%
You're going to be in trouble.

00:06:25.460 --> 00:06:27.530 align:middle line:84%
So they become natural
lightning rods.

00:06:27.530 --> 00:06:29.210 align:middle line:90%
I think that's one reason.

00:06:29.210 --> 00:06:32.570 align:middle line:84%
I think another reason is
that it's natural in us

00:06:32.570 --> 00:06:34.529 align:middle line:84%
to want to share our
pain with others.

00:06:34.529 --> 00:06:36.070 align:middle line:84%
But I think it's so
important to make

00:06:36.070 --> 00:06:39.150 align:middle line:84%
it clear to the other
person-- I'm not blaming you

00:06:39.150 --> 00:06:40.390 align:middle line:90%
for my bad day.

00:06:40.390 --> 00:06:41.170 align:middle line:90%
I'd love it if--

00:06:41.170 --> 00:06:41.520 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You'd listen.

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:43.478 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: In other words,
I'd call that-- yeah.

00:06:43.478 --> 00:06:45.220 align:middle line:84%
It's responsibly
sharing your experience.

00:06:45.220 --> 00:06:49.224 align:middle line:84%
This is how it is for me, and
I'm not blaming you for it.

00:06:49.224 --> 00:06:51.140 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And I don't need
you to fix it, I just

00:06:51.140 --> 00:06:51.880 align:middle line:90%
need you to listen.

00:06:51.880 --> 00:06:52.240 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:06:52.240 --> 00:06:52.830 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:06:52.830 --> 00:06:54.360 align:middle line:84%
I think especially,
as studies show,

00:06:54.360 --> 00:06:57.120 align:middle line:84%
that statement is very
useful for men to hear,

00:06:57.120 --> 00:06:59.840 align:middle line:84%
because otherwise-- again, as
a generalization about gender,

00:06:59.840 --> 00:07:01.339 align:middle line:84%
you have to be
always careful about.

00:07:01.339 --> 00:07:03.780 align:middle line:84%
But still, if most
men don't hear

00:07:03.780 --> 00:07:05.470 align:middle line:84%
that you don't need
to fix it, they're

00:07:05.470 --> 00:07:06.760 align:middle line:90%
going to want to fix it.

00:07:06.760 --> 00:07:08.530 align:middle line:84%
A lot out of
because they're very

00:07:08.530 --> 00:07:12.860 align:middle line:84%
moved by the upset or
pain of their partner,

00:07:12.860 --> 00:07:14.460 align:middle line:84%
whether they're in
a gay relationship

00:07:14.460 --> 00:07:15.700 align:middle line:90%
or a heterosexual one.

00:07:15.700 --> 00:07:16.780 align:middle line:90%
They want to fix it.

00:07:16.780 --> 00:07:18.850 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You have to put
the disclaimer out first.

00:07:18.850 --> 00:07:24.490 align:middle line:84%
But that natural ability for men
to want to solve, rescue, fix,

00:07:24.490 --> 00:07:27.030 align:middle line:84%
be the hero is,
again, in the brain.

00:07:27.030 --> 00:07:28.280 align:middle line:90%
It's part of the biochemistry.

00:07:28.280 --> 00:07:30.290 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Sure, and
it's also culture, too.

00:07:30.290 --> 00:07:30.645 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Culture.

00:07:30.645 --> 00:07:31.311 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Right.

00:07:31.311 --> 00:07:31.960 align:middle line:90%
Exactly.

00:07:31.960 --> 00:07:33.660 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's
helpful to realize

00:07:33.660 --> 00:07:36.640 align:middle line:84%
that it's well-intended at
bottom-- usually, not always.

00:07:36.640 --> 00:07:38.380 align:middle line:84%
But it's usually
well-intended by bottom,

00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:39.800 align:middle line:90%
even if it's obnoxious.

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:42.190 align:middle line:84%
And it's good to
say, no, I don't

00:07:42.190 --> 00:07:45.720 align:middle line:84%
need you to solve my problem, I
just want to connect with you.

00:07:45.720 --> 00:07:46.390 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:07:46.390 --> 00:07:47.520 align:middle line:90%
That's so interesting.

00:07:47.520 --> 00:07:50.140 align:middle line:84%
That a whole nother
conversation about men and women

00:07:50.140 --> 00:07:51.640 align:middle line:84%
and how we interpret
each other's

00:07:51.640 --> 00:07:54.120 align:middle line:84%
conversations and
communication differently.

00:07:54.120 --> 00:07:57.100 align:middle line:84%
But women could look at that as,
oh, you're basically telling me

00:07:57.100 --> 00:07:58.700 align:middle line:84%
I'm stupid and I don't
know how to do it myself.

00:07:58.700 --> 00:07:59.310 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Totally.

00:07:59.310 --> 00:08:01.393 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I don't need to
be the damsel in distress.

00:08:01.393 --> 00:08:02.460 align:middle line:90%
So we overreact.

00:08:02.460 --> 00:08:03.260 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:08:03.260 --> 00:08:05.520 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So it goes
back to the grievances.

00:08:05.520 --> 00:08:09.520 align:middle line:84%
So what do you find is the
main cause of discontent

00:08:09.520 --> 00:08:10.235 align:middle line:90%
in relationships?

00:08:10.235 --> 00:08:12.776 align:middle line:90%


00:08:12.776 --> 00:08:13.720 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Wow.

00:08:13.720 --> 00:08:16.247 align:middle line:84%
So we're talking about adult
romantic relationships?

00:08:16.247 --> 00:08:17.122 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Let's-- yeah.

00:08:17.122 --> 00:08:17.622 align:middle line:90%
Start there.

00:08:17.622 --> 00:08:19.840 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Keep it there.

00:08:19.840 --> 00:08:22.550 align:middle line:84%
I think the main
source of discontent

00:08:22.550 --> 00:08:25.130 align:middle line:84%
is feeling let down by
your partner in some way.

00:08:25.130 --> 00:08:26.450 align:middle line:90%
And often it's really subtle.

00:08:26.450 --> 00:08:26.670 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Unsupported.

00:08:26.670 --> 00:08:28.336 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Like you
look at your partner,

00:08:28.336 --> 00:08:29.532 align:middle line:90%
and your partner looks away.

00:08:29.532 --> 00:08:30.990 align:middle line:84%
You don't feel like
your partner is

00:08:30.990 --> 00:08:33.539 align:middle line:84%
being willing to give you
the gift of attention.

00:08:33.539 --> 00:08:37.970 align:middle line:84%
Or you realize-- it's
very common for women--

00:08:37.970 --> 00:08:40.260 align:middle line:84%
that you're doing a lot
more of the daily grind--

00:08:40.260 --> 00:08:45.300 align:middle line:84%
more dishes, more childcare,
more laundry, what have you--

00:08:45.300 --> 00:08:46.760 align:middle line:90%
and it just doesn't feel fair.

00:08:46.760 --> 00:08:48.380 align:middle line:84%
You feel let down
by the other person.

00:08:48.380 --> 00:08:49.600 align:middle line:90%
Or, flip it the other way.

00:08:49.600 --> 00:08:52.345 align:middle line:84%
Again, in a common pattern in
a heterosexual relationship,

00:08:52.345 --> 00:08:55.510 align:middle line:84%
the man feeling let down
by his partner who's

00:08:55.510 --> 00:08:57.860 align:middle line:84%
no longer very interested
in him as a lover,

00:08:57.860 --> 00:09:01.096 align:middle line:84%
or doesn't bring that
dimension to their life--

00:09:01.096 --> 00:09:05.170 align:middle line:84%
not just for the few
dozen minutes every week

00:09:05.170 --> 00:09:08.130 align:middle line:84%
that they're actually erotically
involved with each other.

00:09:08.130 --> 00:09:10.560 align:middle line:84%
So my larger point is it's
around feeling let down.

00:09:10.560 --> 00:09:14.350 align:middle line:84%
And so one thing that I try
to do on my side of the street

00:09:14.350 --> 00:09:18.110 align:middle line:84%
is really zero in on what
I call unilateral virtue.

00:09:18.110 --> 00:09:20.130 align:middle line:84%
In other words, how can
I be the best partner

00:09:20.130 --> 00:09:24.270 align:middle line:84%
I can be, within my own code as
to what I see is appropriate,

00:09:24.270 --> 00:09:29.530 align:middle line:84%
and you just zero out, line
out, the maximum reasonable

00:09:29.530 --> 00:09:32.260 align:middle line:84%
responsibility I can take
for your grievances with me.

00:09:32.260 --> 00:09:33.740 align:middle line:84%
How can I give
you the max that I

00:09:33.740 --> 00:09:35.550 align:middle line:84%
can give you, that's
reasonable for me

00:09:35.550 --> 00:09:38.310 align:middle line:84%
to do it, and then do it
again and again and again?

00:09:38.310 --> 00:09:40.120 align:middle line:90%
And that's good for me.

00:09:40.120 --> 00:09:42.630 align:middle line:84%
It's also benevolent and
virtuous and stuff like that,

00:09:42.630 --> 00:09:44.517 align:middle line:84%
but that's your
best-on strategy to get

00:09:44.517 --> 00:09:45.850 align:middle line:90%
what you need from your partner.

00:09:45.850 --> 00:09:48.540 align:middle line:84%
I see so many people-- I've
been a long-time therapist,

00:09:48.540 --> 00:09:51.200 align:middle line:84%
including couples counselor,
and I see so many couples,

00:09:51.200 --> 00:09:52.490 align:middle line:84%
they're just waiting
for the other person

00:09:52.490 --> 00:09:53.230 align:middle line:90%
to make their move.

00:09:53.230 --> 00:09:54.563 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: To say that wrong thing.

00:09:54.563 --> 00:09:56.800 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Yeah, and I
think break the deadlock.

00:09:56.800 --> 00:09:58.520 align:middle line:84%
You take care of your
side of the street.

00:09:58.520 --> 00:10:01.040 align:middle line:84%
Let your partner take care of
his or her side of the street.

00:10:01.040 --> 00:10:02.370 align:middle line:84%
And things are going
to be a lot better.

00:10:02.370 --> 00:10:03.260 align:middle line:90%
So that's one thing.

00:10:03.260 --> 00:10:05.234 align:middle line:84%
And the other is, I
try to help myself--

00:10:05.234 --> 00:10:06.650 align:middle line:84%
this is where we're
probably going

00:10:06.650 --> 00:10:09.990 align:middle line:84%
to go in the conversation-- be
resourced inside myself, which

00:10:09.990 --> 00:10:13.670 align:middle line:84%
means changing my brain
for the better over time

00:10:13.670 --> 00:10:17.430 align:middle line:84%
to have the capability to
really hear your grievances,

00:10:17.430 --> 00:10:19.870 align:middle line:84%
including the
topspin, including,

00:10:19.870 --> 00:10:21.940 align:middle line:84%
honestly, the unfair
aspects of it.

00:10:21.940 --> 00:10:25.000 align:middle line:84%
Because you're revved up,
and that's just how it is.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.240 align:middle line:84%
To stay present with
it and not feel so

00:10:27.240 --> 00:10:29.530 align:middle line:84%
flooded by it that I have
to go to war with you

00:10:29.530 --> 00:10:30.830 align:middle line:90%
to make it go away.

00:10:30.830 --> 00:10:31.410 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:10:31.410 --> 00:10:31.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:10:31.530 --> 00:10:31.590 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:10:31.590 --> 00:10:31.770 align:middle line:90%
Interesting.

00:10:31.770 --> 00:10:32.840 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: You know,
there's a classic line--

00:10:32.840 --> 00:10:34.700 align:middle line:90%
fences make for good neighbors.

00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:36.510 align:middle line:84%
The more centered
one is over here

00:10:36.510 --> 00:10:39.350 align:middle line:84%
and the more resourced one is
over here-- much research shows

00:10:39.350 --> 00:10:42.341 align:middle line:84%
this is true-- the more intimate
we can be with each other.

00:10:42.341 --> 00:10:44.590 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Is that where your
Buddhist practices come in,

00:10:44.590 --> 00:10:47.694 align:middle line:84%
where you really learn
how to be centered?

00:10:47.694 --> 00:10:49.860 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: I think in the
combination, the sweet spot

00:10:49.860 --> 00:10:52.640 align:middle line:84%
of compassion and
equanimity-- in other words,

00:10:52.640 --> 00:10:56.370 align:middle line:84%
where you're both-- you really
let your heart open enough

00:10:56.370 --> 00:10:58.610 align:middle line:90%
to feel the other person.

00:10:58.610 --> 00:11:02.580 align:middle line:84%
I think many, many people don't
feel resourced enough inside

00:11:02.580 --> 00:11:05.910 align:middle line:84%
to actually let their heart
become as wide as it naturally

00:11:05.910 --> 00:11:08.251 align:middle line:84%
would be, because they just
feel overwhelmed by it.

00:11:08.251 --> 00:11:08.750 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:11:08.750 --> 00:11:09.750 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Or they get
caught up in feeling

00:11:09.750 --> 00:11:12.480 align:middle line:84%
guilty about the issue of the
other person and so forth.

00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:16.730 align:middle line:84%
So the art is to have
your heart be super open.

00:11:16.730 --> 00:11:20.270 align:middle line:84%
But to sustain that, you also
need to have some equanimity.

00:11:20.270 --> 00:11:22.730 align:middle line:84%
You need to be able to realize
that your suffering is not

00:11:22.730 --> 00:11:23.670 align:middle line:90%
my own.

00:11:23.670 --> 00:11:27.160 align:middle line:84%
Of the thousands of causes
upstream at this moment

00:11:27.160 --> 00:11:30.550 align:middle line:84%
that are causing your suffering,
very few them, if any,

00:11:30.550 --> 00:11:32.530 align:middle line:90%
have my name on them.

00:11:32.530 --> 00:11:33.890 align:middle line:90%
So that plays.

00:11:33.890 --> 00:11:36.542 align:middle line:84%
But the broader point though,
is to resource yourself.

00:11:36.542 --> 00:11:38.250 align:middle line:84%
And that's where I'm
much more interested

00:11:38.250 --> 00:11:39.910 align:middle line:84%
in the neuropsychology
of learning,

00:11:39.910 --> 00:11:42.020 align:middle line:84%
because that's what's
really skillful.

00:11:42.020 --> 00:11:44.186 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I love that you're
saying resource yourself.

00:11:44.186 --> 00:11:46.900 align:middle line:84%
So how do you-- I mean, maybe
you're overwhelmed, burnt out,

00:11:46.900 --> 00:11:49.040 align:middle line:84%
and then there's more
demands and more demands

00:11:49.040 --> 00:11:50.310 align:middle line:90%
that are put on you.

00:11:50.310 --> 00:11:52.740 align:middle line:84%
How do you resource
your own happiness?

00:11:52.740 --> 00:11:55.450 align:middle line:84%
You say that you can
hardwire happiness.

00:11:55.450 --> 00:11:56.443 align:middle line:90%
How?

00:11:56.443 --> 00:11:57.065 align:middle line:90%
How?

00:11:57.065 --> 00:11:59.190 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Let's put it in
a relationship situation.

00:11:59.190 --> 00:12:00.940 align:middle line:84%
So we'll just use
a concrete example.

00:12:00.940 --> 00:12:05.830 align:middle line:84%
Let's say you're with
someone who is feeling like

00:12:05.830 --> 00:12:10.040 align:middle line:84%
you're-- let's say she feels
that he is letting her down.

00:12:10.040 --> 00:12:10.790 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:12:10.790 --> 00:12:11.390 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: OK?

00:12:11.390 --> 00:12:13.940 align:middle line:84%
And so for him to
respond to that,

00:12:13.940 --> 00:12:16.460 align:middle line:84%
he needs to have
resources inside.

00:12:16.460 --> 00:12:20.930 align:middle line:84%
He needs to have the ability
to sustain compassion for her.

00:12:20.930 --> 00:12:25.080 align:middle line:84%
He needs the ability to actually
assert himself in a real way.

00:12:25.080 --> 00:12:28.781 align:middle line:84%
Because if you can't say no,
your yes doesn't mean anything.

00:12:28.781 --> 00:12:29.280 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:12:29.280 --> 00:12:30.540 align:middle line:90%
That's a powerful statement.

00:12:30.540 --> 00:12:31.400 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:12:31.400 --> 00:12:36.110 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Yeah, for women often,
as well as for men, as well

00:12:36.110 --> 00:12:37.430 align:middle line:90%
as other kinds of resources.

00:12:37.430 --> 00:12:40.970 align:middle line:84%
So in that context, then, what
would be some of the resources

00:12:40.970 --> 00:12:42.830 align:middle line:84%
a person might
want to draw upon?

00:12:42.830 --> 00:12:46.370 align:middle line:84%
You know, feeling
centered, feeling loving,

00:12:46.370 --> 00:12:49.150 align:middle line:84%
having a sense of
appropriate boundaries,

00:12:49.150 --> 00:12:52.610 align:middle line:84%
being able to sustain
empathy for the other person,

00:12:52.610 --> 00:12:54.580 align:middle line:84%
having some control of
their own attention--

00:12:54.580 --> 00:12:57.890 align:middle line:84%
to be able to stay present
rather than wander off.

00:12:57.890 --> 00:12:59.230 align:middle line:90%
Those are just normal resources.

00:12:59.230 --> 00:13:00.710 align:middle line:90%
Resources is a fancy word.

00:13:00.710 --> 00:13:02.156 align:middle line:84%
I use the phrase
inner strengths--

00:13:02.156 --> 00:13:04.280 align:middle line:84%
the good stuff we want to
grow inside of ourselves.

00:13:04.280 --> 00:13:04.779 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:13:04.779 --> 00:13:05.364 align:middle line:90%
Cultivate.

00:13:05.364 --> 00:13:06.780 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: So then
the question is,

00:13:06.780 --> 00:13:08.285 align:middle line:84%
how do you grow it
inside yourself?

00:13:08.285 --> 00:13:08.785 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:13:08.785 --> 00:13:11.690 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Because, again,
studies show about a third,

00:13:11.690 --> 00:13:14.990 align:middle line:84%
roughly, of the causes of
the resources that people

00:13:14.990 --> 00:13:17.050 align:middle line:84%
have are based in
their genetics.

00:13:17.050 --> 00:13:17.670 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:17.670 --> 00:13:20.020 align:middle line:84%
That means that two
thirds, in principle,

00:13:20.020 --> 00:13:21.280 align:middle line:90%
is under our own power.

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:21.800 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:13:21.800 --> 00:13:22.080 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:13:22.080 --> 00:13:22.690 align:middle line:90%
And I'm all for that part.

00:13:22.690 --> 00:13:23.250 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I'll take it.

00:13:23.250 --> 00:13:23.875 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:13:23.875 --> 00:13:24.730 align:middle line:90%
Exactly right.

00:13:24.730 --> 00:13:25.230 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:13:25.230 --> 00:13:27.210 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: And so
the good news is

00:13:27.210 --> 00:13:30.180 align:middle line:84%
that you can grow
resources inside yourself.

00:13:30.180 --> 00:13:33.630 align:middle line:84%
And the real news is that it's
your responsibility to do it

00:13:33.630 --> 00:13:34.650 align:middle line:90%
or not, right?

00:13:34.650 --> 00:13:37.270 align:middle line:84%
So then I get into-- and maybe
we could talk about that.

00:13:37.270 --> 00:13:40.320 align:middle line:84%
How do you grow
resources in your brain

00:13:40.320 --> 00:13:42.000 align:middle line:84%
so that, as you go
through life, instead

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:45.520 align:middle line:84%
of your learning curve being
kind of flat, like that, no.

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:47.250 align:middle line:90%
You're really steep.

00:13:47.250 --> 00:13:48.780 align:middle line:90%
You learn how to learn.

00:13:48.780 --> 00:13:50.305 align:middle line:90%
You get good at getting good.

00:13:50.305 --> 00:13:52.430 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And those are the
memories and the learning

00:13:52.430 --> 00:13:55.027 align:middle line:84%
strategies that you remember
even more, because they've

00:13:55.027 --> 00:13:56.910 align:middle line:84%
got emotion attached
to them, right?

00:13:56.910 --> 00:13:57.610 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:13:57.610 --> 00:14:01.540 align:middle line:84%
Really good news, actually, is
that these inner strengths-- so

00:14:01.540 --> 00:14:02.690 align:middle line:90%
let's use examples of them.

00:14:02.690 --> 00:14:06.870 align:middle line:84%
Mindfulness, compassion,
patience, determination,

00:14:06.870 --> 00:14:11.530 align:middle line:84%
resilience, abilities, feeling
loved, feeling of self-worth,

00:14:11.530 --> 00:14:13.770 align:middle line:84%
feeling like genuinely--
sorry to bang

00:14:13.770 --> 00:14:16.599 align:middle line:84%
the microphone there-- feeling
like a genuinely good person

00:14:16.599 --> 00:14:17.390 align:middle line:90%
deep in your heart.

00:14:17.390 --> 00:14:20.410 align:middle line:84%
Kind of the final taboo is
to acknowledge to yourself

00:14:20.410 --> 00:14:22.980 align:middle line:84%
that you really actually
are a good person-- not

00:14:22.980 --> 00:14:24.900 align:middle line:84%
a perfect person,
but a good person.

00:14:24.900 --> 00:14:25.400 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:14:25.400 --> 00:14:25.670 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yesh.

00:14:25.670 --> 00:14:25.940 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: OK.

00:14:25.940 --> 00:14:27.490 align:middle line:84%
So these are different
kinds of resources.

00:14:27.490 --> 00:14:29.656 align:middle line:84%
They're also what we'd like
to grow in our children,

00:14:29.656 --> 00:14:32.500 align:middle line:84%
or if we work with other people
as a coach or a therapist

00:14:32.500 --> 00:14:34.960 align:middle line:84%
or a health care
provider, a teacher.

00:14:34.960 --> 00:14:36.470 align:middle line:90%
We want to grow that in others.

00:14:36.470 --> 00:14:36.970 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:14:36.970 --> 00:14:38.640 align:middle line:84%
So this is the good
stuff we all want.

00:14:38.640 --> 00:14:39.460 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:14:39.460 --> 00:14:42.090 align:middle line:84%
How do you get it
into your brain?

00:14:42.090 --> 00:14:45.430 align:middle line:84%
So here, bottom line,
it's a two-stage process.

00:14:45.430 --> 00:14:47.800 align:middle line:84%
First, you need to
have an experience

00:14:47.800 --> 00:14:51.490 align:middle line:84%
of this inner strength,
which is usually enjoyable.

00:14:51.490 --> 00:14:53.070 align:middle line:90%
It actually feels good.

00:14:53.070 --> 00:14:54.490 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It has a good emotion.

00:14:54.490 --> 00:14:54.640 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:55.650 align:middle line:90%
And it's motivating to do it.

00:14:55.650 --> 00:14:56.941 align:middle line:90%
It feels good to feel grateful.

00:14:56.941 --> 00:14:58.880 align:middle line:84%
It feels good to be
determined and strong.

00:14:58.880 --> 00:15:00.860 align:middle line:90%
It feels good to relax.

00:15:00.860 --> 00:15:03.140 align:middle line:90%
It feels good to be loving.

00:15:03.140 --> 00:15:04.840 align:middle line:90%
It feels good to be loved.

00:15:04.840 --> 00:15:07.020 align:middle line:84%
All of these are various
kinds of inner strengths.

00:15:07.020 --> 00:15:09.180 align:middle line:84%
So that's really neat to
notice in the first place.

00:15:09.180 --> 00:15:09.680 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:15:09.680 --> 00:15:12.550 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: These are
usually sweet experiences.

00:15:12.550 --> 00:15:16.730 align:middle line:84%
And then second, most important,
don't waste them on your brain.

00:15:16.730 --> 00:15:20.960 align:middle line:84%
You need to stay with
the activated experience

00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:24.740 align:middle line:84%
to install it in some sort
of change in neural structure

00:15:24.740 --> 00:15:25.890 align:middle line:90%
or function.

00:15:25.890 --> 00:15:29.619 align:middle line:84%
If you don't install it,
it's wasted on your brain.

00:15:29.619 --> 00:15:30.160 align:middle line:90%
It might be--

00:15:30.160 --> 00:15:32.201 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Oh, so if you
don't actually practice it.

00:15:32.201 --> 00:15:33.124 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Take it in.

00:15:33.124 --> 00:15:34.290 align:middle line:90%
If you don't let it sink in.

00:15:34.290 --> 00:15:36.820 align:middle line:84%
If you don't take the dozen
or so seconds, loosely,

00:15:36.820 --> 00:15:39.210 align:middle line:84%
to help it sink
in, you're learning

00:15:39.210 --> 00:15:42.280 align:middle line:84%
from this moment of
feeling appreciated.

00:15:42.280 --> 00:15:43.830 align:middle line:90%
I feel appreciated by you.

00:15:43.830 --> 00:15:45.980 align:middle line:90%
What will I do with this moment?

00:15:45.980 --> 00:15:47.580 align:middle line:90%
Or, this is interesting.

00:15:47.580 --> 00:15:48.913 align:middle line:90%
What will I do with that moment?

00:15:48.913 --> 00:15:51.502 align:middle line:84%
When a person finishes
the dishes, it's done.

00:15:51.502 --> 00:15:53.210 align:middle line:84%
You have an opportunity
to feel complete.

00:15:53.210 --> 00:15:56.721 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Take the time to say
thank you to your partner.

00:15:56.721 --> 00:15:57.220 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:15:57.220 --> 00:16:00.480 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: To be intimate
with your own self

00:16:00.480 --> 00:16:03.250 align:middle line:84%
as well as intimate with
others, to really receive

00:16:03.250 --> 00:16:06.400 align:middle line:84%
the experience and
help it sink into you.

00:16:06.400 --> 00:16:09.740 align:middle line:84%
So the fancy-- it's a two-stage
process, from short-term memory

00:16:09.740 --> 00:16:13.870 align:middle line:84%
buffers to long-term
storage, from state to trait,

00:16:13.870 --> 00:16:16.320 align:middle line:90%
activation to installation.

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:17.930 align:middle line:84%
And it's kind of
like in real estate.

00:16:17.930 --> 00:16:19.971 align:middle line:84%
You know real estate boils
down to three things--

00:16:19.971 --> 00:16:22.240 align:middle line:90%
location, location, location.

00:16:22.240 --> 00:16:25.430 align:middle line:84%
Learning, including
personal growth learning,

00:16:25.430 --> 00:16:28.230 align:middle line:84%
emotional learning,
spiritual learning,

00:16:28.230 --> 00:16:30.750 align:middle line:84%
motivational learning,
life learning,

00:16:30.750 --> 00:16:33.260 align:middle line:84%
boils down to three
things-- installation,

00:16:33.260 --> 00:16:34.880 align:middle line:90%
installation, installation.

00:16:34.880 --> 00:16:35.380 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh.

00:16:35.380 --> 00:16:36.040 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:16:36.040 --> 00:16:38.790 align:middle line:84%
Well, let's take a look
here at Rick Hanson talking

00:16:38.790 --> 00:16:40.652 align:middle line:90%
about hardwiring happiness.

00:16:40.652 --> 00:16:41.360 align:middle line:90%
Take a look here.

00:16:41.360 --> 00:16:55.250 align:middle line:90%


00:16:55.250 --> 00:16:57.630 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Wow.

00:16:57.630 --> 00:16:59.350 align:middle line:84%
So what I want to
do here if I could

00:16:59.350 --> 00:17:04.740 align:middle line:84%
is share with you a very
simple yet powerful method,

00:17:04.740 --> 00:17:09.000 align:middle line:84%
grounded in neuroscience, for
turning passing experiences

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:13.000 align:middle line:84%
into lasting structure, useful
structure, inside our brain.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:16.430 align:middle line:84%
In other words, turning
experiences into the happiness

00:17:16.430 --> 00:17:18.770 align:middle line:84%
or the resilience or the
other inner strengths

00:17:18.770 --> 00:17:21.089 align:middle line:84%
that we really want
inside ourselves.

00:17:21.089 --> 00:17:24.760 align:middle line:84%
I sort of stumbled on this
method when I was in college.

00:17:24.760 --> 00:17:27.260 align:middle line:84%
But to explain the context, I
have to take you back a little

00:17:27.260 --> 00:17:30.880 align:middle line:84%
before, into my own
up and down childhood.

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:36.230 align:middle line:84%
So I grew up in a loving home--
good parents, intact family.

00:17:36.230 --> 00:17:38.670 align:middle line:84%
But I was very, very young
going through school.

00:17:38.670 --> 00:17:40.740 align:middle line:84%
I have a late birthday
and I skipped a grade.

00:17:40.740 --> 00:17:45.700 align:middle line:84%
And that combined with my kind
of shy and seriously dorky

00:17:45.700 --> 00:17:48.600 align:middle line:84%
temperament-- you
know, skinny, glasses,

00:17:48.600 --> 00:17:50.680 align:middle line:84%
picked last for baseball,
the whole thing.

00:17:50.680 --> 00:17:54.210 align:middle line:84%
Well, what it led to
were lots of experiences

00:17:54.210 --> 00:17:58.360 align:middle line:84%
of being left out or put down
by the other kids in school.

00:17:58.360 --> 00:18:01.560 align:middle line:84%
Now, what happened to me
was very small compared to,

00:18:01.560 --> 00:18:04.300 align:middle line:84%
unfortunately, what happens
to many, many other people.

00:18:04.300 --> 00:18:07.290 align:middle line:84%
But we all have normal
needs to feel cared for,

00:18:07.290 --> 00:18:08.450 align:middle line:90%
to feel cared about.

00:18:08.450 --> 00:18:11.350 align:middle line:84%
We are the most profoundly
social species on the planet.

00:18:11.350 --> 00:18:15.100 align:middle line:84%
As we evolved in the Serengeti,
exile was a death sentence.

00:18:15.100 --> 00:18:16.590 align:middle line:90%
Causes have effects.

00:18:16.590 --> 00:18:20.830 align:middle line:84%
And if we don't get the supplies
that we need, bit by bit,

00:18:20.830 --> 00:18:23.440 align:middle line:84%
it's kind of like we're
living on a thin soup.

00:18:23.440 --> 00:18:27.140 align:middle line:84%
You can survive, you can make
it, but there's a hollowness,

00:18:27.140 --> 00:18:28.660 align:middle line:90%
an emptiness inside.

00:18:28.660 --> 00:18:31.020 align:middle line:84%
In my own case--
hopefully this will work.

00:18:31.020 --> 00:18:31.860 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:18:31.860 --> 00:18:35.580 align:middle line:84%
I ended up with lots of bad
thoughts and feelings inside

00:18:35.580 --> 00:18:37.200 align:middle line:90%
of me as a result.

00:18:37.200 --> 00:18:38.680 align:middle line:90%
Then I went off to college.

00:18:38.680 --> 00:18:42.380 align:middle line:84%
And I began to notice
something really

00:18:42.380 --> 00:18:44.160 align:middle line:90%
powerful and interesting.

00:18:44.160 --> 00:18:46.780 align:middle line:84%
Some small good
thing would happen--

00:18:46.780 --> 00:18:49.080 align:middle line:84%
you know, a girl would
smile at me in the elevator,

00:18:49.080 --> 00:18:51.840 align:middle line:84%
some guy would throw me the
football in intramural football

00:18:51.840 --> 00:18:53.379 align:middle line:90%
and say, "good catch, Hanson."

00:18:53.379 --> 00:18:54.670 align:middle line:90%
You know, that was really good.

00:18:54.670 --> 00:18:57.620 align:middle line:84%
Or guys would invite me to
go out for pizza-- you know,

00:18:57.620 --> 00:18:59.130 align:middle line:90%
basic stuff of everyday life.

00:18:59.130 --> 00:19:01.300 align:middle line:84%
And then I would
have an experience.

00:19:01.300 --> 00:19:03.930 align:middle line:84%
I would feel a little
included or a little wanted,

00:19:03.930 --> 00:19:05.490 align:middle line:90%
a little appreciated.

00:19:05.490 --> 00:19:08.330 align:middle line:84%
Then the question is, what
would I do with that experience?

00:19:08.330 --> 00:19:10.060 align:middle line:84%
If I dealt with
it like I usually

00:19:10.060 --> 00:19:14.350 align:middle line:84%
did, which was to kind of
ignore it, let it pass along,

00:19:14.350 --> 00:19:16.660 align:middle line:84%
I kept feeling lonely
and inadequate.

00:19:16.660 --> 00:19:21.390 align:middle line:84%
But I began to notice that if
I did something different, if I

00:19:21.390 --> 00:19:25.160 align:middle line:84%
stayed with it a dozen
or so seconds in a row,

00:19:25.160 --> 00:19:27.430 align:middle line:84%
it felt like something
was gradually

00:19:27.430 --> 00:19:30.170 align:middle line:84%
coming into me that
was actually good.

00:19:30.170 --> 00:19:33.630 align:middle line:84%
And I began feeling better
and better and better

00:19:33.630 --> 00:19:35.220 align:middle line:90%
and more confident.

00:19:35.220 --> 00:19:39.230 align:middle line:84%
Any single time I did this
wasn't a mind-blowing moment.

00:19:39.230 --> 00:19:40.950 align:middle line:84%
I had a few of those
through other means.

00:19:40.950 --> 00:19:45.600 align:middle line:84%
But the good things really
did add up over time for me,

00:19:45.600 --> 00:19:46.640 align:middle line:90%
definitely.

00:19:46.640 --> 00:19:50.900 align:middle line:84%
And now, years later, many years
later, as a neuropsychologist,

00:19:50.900 --> 00:19:54.210 align:middle line:84%
I began to understand
what I was actually doing.

00:19:54.210 --> 00:19:56.080 align:middle line:90%
I wasn't just changing my mind.

00:19:56.080 --> 00:19:58.200 align:middle line:84%
I was actually
changing my brain.

00:19:58.200 --> 00:20:00.490 align:middle line:84%
That's because, as the
neuroscientists say,

00:20:00.490 --> 00:20:03.650 align:middle line:84%
neurons that fire
together wire together.

00:20:03.650 --> 00:20:07.560 align:middle line:84%
Passing mental states become
lasting neural traits.

00:20:07.560 --> 00:20:11.080 align:middle line:84%
Bit by bit, I was actually
weaving these resources

00:20:11.080 --> 00:20:15.260 align:middle line:84%
into the fabric of my brain,
and therefore my life.

00:20:15.260 --> 00:20:18.340 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So let's talk
about how we can actually

00:20:18.340 --> 00:20:20.830 align:middle line:84%
reconstruct memories
in our brain.

00:20:20.830 --> 00:20:21.947 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Sure.

00:20:21.947 --> 00:20:23.530 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: We can take
bad, old memories,

00:20:23.530 --> 00:20:26.180 align:middle line:84%
and can you actually really
change them in your brain?

00:20:26.180 --> 00:20:27.850 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Oh, completely.

00:20:27.850 --> 00:20:30.450 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You can take the heat
off of them, or are they just--

00:20:30.450 --> 00:20:32.658 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: You'll never forget
what actually happened,

00:20:32.658 --> 00:20:35.860 align:middle line:84%
but the charge on what happened,
and given the negativity bias,

00:20:35.860 --> 00:20:37.690 align:middle line:84%
the over-learning
from what happened,

00:20:37.690 --> 00:20:41.700 align:middle line:84%
and ideas or behaviors that were
useful when you were 10 years

00:20:41.700 --> 00:20:43.206 align:middle line:90%
old or 10 months old--

00:20:43.206 --> 00:20:44.580 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Or the
decisions that you

00:20:44.580 --> 00:20:45.910 align:middle line:90%
made as a result of those, yes.

00:20:45.910 --> 00:20:46.909 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Exactly right.

00:20:46.909 --> 00:20:48.316 align:middle line:90%
Those can be cleared away.

00:20:48.316 --> 00:20:50.190 align:middle line:84%
So maybe I'll give you
an example, all right?

00:20:50.190 --> 00:20:50.810 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:20:50.810 --> 00:20:51.351 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: OK.

00:20:51.351 --> 00:20:53.440 align:middle line:84%
So one thing to
do-- three things.

00:20:53.440 --> 00:20:54.350 align:middle line:90%
Very simple.

00:20:54.350 --> 00:20:56.190 align:middle line:90%
Look for good facts.

00:20:56.190 --> 00:20:57.030 align:middle line:90%
They're real facts.

00:20:57.030 --> 00:20:59.060 align:middle line:84%
I don't believe in
positive thinking;

00:20:59.060 --> 00:21:00.860 align:middle line:84%
I believe in realistic
thinking-- seeing

00:21:00.860 --> 00:21:04.120 align:middle line:84%
the whole mosaic of reality: the
good, the bad, and the neutral.

00:21:04.120 --> 00:21:06.380 align:middle line:84%
And I mean good or bad
not moralistically,

00:21:06.380 --> 00:21:09.720 align:middle line:84%
but good is that which leads
to happiness and welfare

00:21:09.720 --> 00:21:11.020 align:middle line:90%
for yourself and others.

00:21:11.020 --> 00:21:13.110 align:middle line:84%
Bad is that which leads
to suffering and harm.

00:21:13.110 --> 00:21:13.710 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:21:13.710 --> 00:21:16.010 align:middle line:84%
So look for the good
facts in everyday life--

00:21:16.010 --> 00:21:18.460 align:middle line:84%
the flowers that are blooming,
the dishes that are done.

00:21:18.460 --> 00:21:20.510 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Oh, current
life, not in the memory.

00:21:20.510 --> 00:21:20.790 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Correct.

00:21:20.790 --> 00:21:22.456 align:middle line:84%
Or you could look for
them in your past.

00:21:22.456 --> 00:21:25.360 align:middle line:84%
You know, in the past,
people were kind to you.

00:21:25.360 --> 00:21:27.689 align:middle line:84%
In the future, good
facts are likely.

00:21:27.689 --> 00:21:29.230 align:middle line:84%
You're going to get
home this evening

00:21:29.230 --> 00:21:30.572 align:middle line:90%
at the end of a long day.

00:21:30.572 --> 00:21:32.405 align:middle line:84%
So look for good facts,
including good facts

00:21:32.405 --> 00:21:34.570 align:middle line:84%
in yourself-- or,
in a relationship,

00:21:34.570 --> 00:21:36.000 align:middle line:90%
good facts about your partner.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:36.230 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:21:36.230 --> 00:21:37.830 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: I've been
married 31 years,

00:21:37.830 --> 00:21:40.690 align:middle line:84%
and it's easy to kind of take
your partner for granted.

00:21:40.690 --> 00:21:42.300 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's
a useful practice.

00:21:42.300 --> 00:21:43.550 align:middle line:90%
I do this myself.

00:21:43.550 --> 00:21:45.490 align:middle line:84%
I look for good
facts in my partner,

00:21:45.490 --> 00:21:48.310 align:middle line:84%
or I try to see them newly, the
ones I'm already familiar with.

00:21:48.310 --> 00:21:49.130 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Great idea.

00:21:49.130 --> 00:21:49.590 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:21:49.590 --> 00:21:50.030 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:21:50.030 --> 00:21:50.946 align:middle line:90%
So see the good facts.

00:21:50.946 --> 00:21:51.490 align:middle line:90%
Two.

00:21:51.490 --> 00:21:53.240 align:middle line:84%
Let yourself have
a good feeling.

00:21:53.240 --> 00:21:55.300 align:middle line:84%
A lot of times we recognize
the good facts-- oh,

00:21:55.300 --> 00:21:56.450 align:middle line:90%
I got that done.

00:21:56.450 --> 00:21:57.260 align:middle line:90%
Whatever.

00:21:57.260 --> 00:21:57.760 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh.

00:21:57.760 --> 00:21:59.010 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: And the kid hugs me.

00:21:59.010 --> 00:21:59.840 align:middle line:90%
Mommy, I love you.

00:21:59.840 --> 00:22:00.535 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, OK.

00:22:00.535 --> 00:22:01.035 align:middle line:90%
Nice.

00:22:01.035 --> 00:22:01.535 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:22:01.535 --> 00:22:02.156 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:22:02.156 --> 00:22:04.280 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Or, you know, so
your boss says good job,

00:22:04.280 --> 00:22:05.550 align:middle line:90%
and, oh, OK, whatever.

00:22:05.550 --> 00:22:06.050 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:22:06.050 --> 00:22:08.330 align:middle line:84%
You get a tricky
email done-- whatever.

00:22:08.330 --> 00:22:08.830 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:22:08.830 --> 00:22:10.810 align:middle line:90%
Let yourself feel it.

00:22:10.810 --> 00:22:13.700 align:middle line:84%
Because you want to get those
neurons firing together so

00:22:13.700 --> 00:22:16.040 align:middle line:84%
you're actually having
a rich experience.

00:22:16.040 --> 00:22:18.940 align:middle line:90%
And then really take it in.

00:22:18.940 --> 00:22:21.890 align:middle line:84%
Take the extra 10, 20, 30
seconds to kind of marinate

00:22:21.890 --> 00:22:26.640 align:middle line:84%
in the experience, enjoy it,
stay with it, open to it.

00:22:26.640 --> 00:22:28.320 align:middle line:84%
Get those neurons
firing together

00:22:28.320 --> 00:22:30.501 align:middle line:84%
so they really wire that
experience into you.

00:22:30.501 --> 00:22:32.000 align:middle line:84%
So to use that--
want me to give you

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:33.550 align:middle line:84%
a practical example
in a relationship?

00:22:33.550 --> 00:22:33.830 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:22:33.830 --> 00:22:34.006 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: OK.

00:22:34.006 --> 00:22:34.640 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:22:34.640 --> 00:22:39.220 align:middle line:84%
So let's say you're trying
to mend a relationship--

00:22:39.220 --> 00:22:41.990 align:middle line:84%
because, you know, "Rust
Never Sleeps," right?

00:22:41.990 --> 00:22:46.740 align:middle line:84%
The fabric of a relationship is
so easy to fray, cut by cut--

00:22:46.740 --> 00:22:48.390 align:middle line:84%
the death of a
thousand paper cuts.

00:22:48.390 --> 00:22:50.235 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, especially when
you're together for so long,

00:22:50.235 --> 00:22:50.735 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:22:50.735 --> 00:22:51.844 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: And you're busy.

00:22:51.844 --> 00:22:53.885 align:middle line:84%
It's a work relationship,
a family relationship--

00:22:53.885 --> 00:22:55.520 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't
necessarily need to be

00:22:55.520 --> 00:22:57.159 align:middle line:84%
a mate or a romantic
relationship.

00:22:57.159 --> 00:22:57.742 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:22:57.742 --> 00:22:57.880 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:22:57.880 --> 00:22:59.296 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Anyway,
so let's suppose

00:22:59.296 --> 00:23:00.740 align:middle line:84%
you're trying to
repair something,

00:23:00.740 --> 00:23:04.310 align:middle line:84%
and it would be useful
in the repair process

00:23:04.310 --> 00:23:08.370 align:middle line:84%
to feel cared about in ways that
you factually are cared about.

00:23:08.370 --> 00:23:10.000 align:middle line:90%
I'm not making anything up here.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:12.721 align:middle line:84%
So let's say you and I are in
a relationship of some kind.

00:23:12.721 --> 00:23:13.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: All right.

00:23:13.470 --> 00:23:14.950 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: So I
have an opportunity

00:23:14.950 --> 00:23:18.070 align:middle line:84%
to recognize factually that,
oh, you do appreciate me.

00:23:18.070 --> 00:23:20.245 align:middle line:84%
Or, oh, you said
thanks, or, oh, you

00:23:20.245 --> 00:23:22.536 align:middle line:84%
didn't do that annoying thing
because you care about me

00:23:22.536 --> 00:23:26.000 align:middle line:84%
and you're actually sincere
in trying to repair here.

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:27.210 align:middle line:90%
Did I notice that good fact?

00:23:27.210 --> 00:23:27.710 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:23:27.710 --> 00:23:29.680 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Second, did
I let myself feel it?

00:23:29.680 --> 00:23:34.390 align:middle line:84%
And third, can I just kind of
hang out with it, privately

00:23:34.390 --> 00:23:36.890 align:middle line:84%
inside myself--
five, 10, 20 seconds

00:23:36.890 --> 00:23:39.050 align:middle line:90%
in a row, a small little thing.

00:23:39.050 --> 00:23:41.530 align:middle line:84%
And yet, bit by bit, you
can change your brain

00:23:41.530 --> 00:23:42.560 align:middle line:90%
for the better.

00:23:42.560 --> 00:23:44.175 align:middle line:84%
And then, if I want
to heal it-- which

00:23:44.175 --> 00:23:45.550 align:middle line:84%
is kind of where
we started here.

00:23:45.550 --> 00:23:48.290 align:middle line:84%
Let's suppose I haven't
felt so cared about by you.

00:23:48.290 --> 00:23:49.440 align:middle line:90%
Maybe you were mean to me.

00:23:49.440 --> 00:23:51.820 align:middle line:84%
Maybe you betrayed
me in some way.

00:23:51.820 --> 00:23:53.270 align:middle line:90%
Maybe something happened.

00:23:53.270 --> 00:23:57.430 align:middle line:84%
But authentically, truly,
you are more caring today.

00:23:57.430 --> 00:24:00.510 align:middle line:84%
You are trying to mend
this relationship, right.

00:24:00.510 --> 00:24:03.940 align:middle line:84%
What I can do-- and I
use the acronym "HEAL"

00:24:03.940 --> 00:24:05.310 align:middle line:90%
to describe this whole process.

00:24:05.310 --> 00:24:07.964 align:middle line:84%
H-E-A-L. So first you have
to have the experience--

00:24:07.964 --> 00:24:09.630 align:middle line:84%
in my example here,
feeling cared about.

00:24:09.630 --> 00:24:10.129 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK

00:24:10.129 --> 00:24:12.820 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: And then to get it
into the brain, installation,

00:24:12.820 --> 00:24:16.200 align:middle line:84%
I enrich the experience
by feeling it in my body

00:24:16.200 --> 00:24:17.370 align:middle line:90%
and staying with it.

00:24:17.370 --> 00:24:19.470 align:middle line:84%
And it's kind of
private, it's real.

00:24:19.470 --> 00:24:21.750 align:middle line:90%
And I also A for absorb it.

00:24:21.750 --> 00:24:23.770 align:middle line:84%
I sense and intend
it sinking in.

00:24:23.770 --> 00:24:26.620 align:middle line:84%
And then, if I want, I can
link this positive experience

00:24:26.620 --> 00:24:29.650 align:middle line:84%
of feeling cared about-- by the
other person, let's say, here

00:24:29.650 --> 00:24:30.640 align:middle line:90%
and now, today.

00:24:30.640 --> 00:24:33.300 align:middle line:84%
I can link that
positive experience

00:24:33.300 --> 00:24:34.900 align:middle line:90%
to some negative material.

00:24:34.900 --> 00:24:38.290 align:middle line:84%
So have, enrich, absorb,
link gives us "HEAL."

00:24:38.290 --> 00:24:38.790 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Ah.

00:24:38.790 --> 00:24:40.250 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: So in
terms of linking,

00:24:40.250 --> 00:24:43.470 align:middle line:84%
I could feel
appreciated or seen,

00:24:43.470 --> 00:24:45.690 align:middle line:84%
or at least you have good
intentions toward me,

00:24:45.690 --> 00:24:46.430 align:middle line:90%
at minimum.

00:24:46.430 --> 00:24:47.910 align:middle line:90%
So I'm feeling then now.

00:24:47.910 --> 00:24:50.530 align:middle line:84%
And I could also be aware
in the background that

00:24:50.530 --> 00:24:53.360 align:middle line:84%
sense of being let down by
you-- which also might have been

00:24:53.360 --> 00:24:56.010 align:middle line:84%
turbocharged by earlier
life experiences,

00:24:56.010 --> 00:24:58.280 align:middle line:84%
even going back into
childhood when I was let down

00:24:58.280 --> 00:24:59.280 align:middle line:90%
by other people as well.

00:24:59.280 --> 00:24:59.940 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, I see.

00:24:59.940 --> 00:25:02.440 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: So since neurons that
fire together wire together,

00:25:02.440 --> 00:25:05.010 align:middle line:84%
I'm being aware of both of
those things at the same time.

00:25:05.010 --> 00:25:07.910 align:middle line:84%
The positive gradually
associates with the negative,

00:25:07.910 --> 00:25:11.600 align:middle line:84%
soothing it, easing
it, and eventually

00:25:11.600 --> 00:25:13.467 align:middle line:84%
potentially replacing
it altogether.

00:25:13.467 --> 00:25:14.300 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:25:14.300 --> 00:25:16.600 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: And that's
something that any person can

00:25:16.600 --> 00:25:19.890 align:middle line:84%
do in the flow of everyday life,
which I think is fantastic.

00:25:19.890 --> 00:25:21.040 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Absolutely.

00:25:21.040 --> 00:25:24.990 align:middle line:84%
That's how you change a
memory and you over-layer it

00:25:24.990 --> 00:25:26.695 align:middle line:90%
with a positive association.

00:25:26.695 --> 00:25:27.320 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:25:27.320 --> 00:25:29.650 align:middle line:84%
And when yo u say memory,
