00:26:18.700 --> 00:26:22.670 align:middle line:84%
real world-- they actually
have measurably thicker

00:26:22.670 --> 00:26:24.785 align:middle line:90%
brains in certain key regions.

00:26:24.785 --> 00:26:27.429 align:middle line:84%
So the number one region up
here is called the insula.

00:26:27.429 --> 00:26:29.220 align:middle line:84%
It's a part of the
brain-- and again, there

00:26:29.220 --> 00:26:31.210 align:middle line:84%
are two of them--
that is involved

00:26:31.210 --> 00:26:33.090 align:middle line:84%
in what's called
interoception, tuning

00:26:33.090 --> 00:26:35.360 align:middle line:84%
in to the internal
state of your body

00:26:35.360 --> 00:26:37.580 align:middle line:90%
as well as your deep feelings.

00:26:37.580 --> 00:26:39.620 align:middle line:84%
No wonder-- they're
tuning in to themselves.

00:26:39.620 --> 00:26:41.119 align:middle line:84%
Probably a lot of
what they're doing

00:26:41.119 --> 00:26:42.760 align:middle line:84%
is practicing
mindfulness of breathing.

00:26:42.760 --> 00:26:43.880 align:middle line:90%
They're getting in touch.

00:26:43.880 --> 00:26:46.470 align:middle line:84%
They're staying really
present with what's going on.

00:26:46.470 --> 00:26:49.160 align:middle line:84%
No wonder-- they're using,
and therefore they're

00:26:49.160 --> 00:26:52.680 align:middle line:84%
building, much like a muscle,
by analogy, literally.

00:26:52.680 --> 00:26:56.630 align:middle line:84%
They're using it, so they
build it-- the insula.

00:26:56.630 --> 00:26:59.340 align:middle line:84%
The second region is
the frontal regions

00:26:59.340 --> 00:27:02.070 align:middle line:84%
of the prefrontal cortex,
the frontal areas that

00:27:02.070 --> 00:27:04.830 align:middle line:84%
are involved, again, in
controlling attention.

00:27:04.830 --> 00:27:06.770 align:middle line:90%
No surprise here, as well.

00:27:06.770 --> 00:27:10.020 align:middle line:84%
They're using attention, so
they're getting more control

00:27:10.020 --> 00:27:14.010 align:middle line:84%
over it, and they're
strengthening its neural basis.

00:27:14.010 --> 00:27:16.831 align:middle line:84%
The third region up at the
top is somatosensory cortex.

00:27:16.831 --> 00:27:18.330 align:middle line:84%
It's the part that
basically they're

00:27:18.330 --> 00:27:19.640 align:middle line:90%
tuning in to their body.

00:27:19.640 --> 00:27:21.880 align:middle line:84%
It's less relevant
for our purposes.

00:27:21.880 --> 00:27:25.470 align:middle line:84%
The point is that people who
routinely practice something--

00:27:25.470 --> 00:27:30.170 align:middle line:84%
in this particular case,
mindfulness meditation-- build

00:27:30.170 --> 00:27:32.850 align:middle line:84%
up the neural substrates
that are its basis.

00:27:32.850 --> 00:27:36.760 align:middle line:84%
Normally we lose about
10,000 brain cells a day.

00:27:36.760 --> 00:27:41.160 align:middle line:84%
That may sound horrible, but
we were born with 1.1 trillion.

00:27:41.160 --> 00:27:43.930 align:middle line:84%
And we also have
several thousand a day

00:27:43.930 --> 00:27:47.570 align:middle line:84%
born inside mainly
the hippocampus,

00:27:47.570 --> 00:27:51.240 align:middle line:84%
actually, in what's
called neurogenesis.

00:27:51.240 --> 00:27:54.100 align:middle line:84%
So losing 10,000 a day
isn't that big a deal.

00:27:54.100 --> 00:27:56.960 align:middle line:84%
But the net bottom line is
that a typical 80-year-old

00:27:56.960 --> 00:28:00.150 align:middle line:84%
will have lost about
4% of brain mass.

00:28:00.150 --> 00:28:02.050 align:middle line:84%
It's called cortical
thinning with aging.

00:28:02.050 --> 00:28:03.810 align:middle line:90%
It's a normal process.

00:28:03.810 --> 00:28:05.570 align:middle line:84%
So in this study,
there was a comparison

00:28:05.570 --> 00:28:07.910 align:middle line:84%
between the meditators
and the non-meditators.

00:28:07.910 --> 00:28:09.800 align:middle line:84%
The meditators are
the blue circles.

00:28:09.800 --> 00:28:13.660 align:middle line:84%
The non-meditators are the
red squares, age-matched

00:28:13.660 --> 00:28:15.080 align:middle line:90%
and so forth.

00:28:15.080 --> 00:28:16.770 align:middle line:84%
This was not a
longitudinal study.

00:28:16.770 --> 00:28:20.610 align:middle line:84%
It was a cohort study with
some good statistical controls.

00:28:20.610 --> 00:28:23.740 align:middle line:84%
The people who are the
red squares, the controls,

00:28:23.740 --> 00:28:25.740 align:middle line:84%
experienced normal
cortical thinning

00:28:25.740 --> 00:28:27.810 align:middle line:84%
in these three
regions of interest,

00:28:27.810 --> 00:28:30.800 align:middle line:84%
whereas the people who
routinely meditated and worked

00:28:30.800 --> 00:28:34.110 align:middle line:84%
that muscle, quote
unquote, did not experience

00:28:34.110 --> 00:28:35.550 align:middle line:84%
cortical thinning
in that region.

00:28:35.550 --> 00:28:38.520 align:middle line:84%
And they're the blue circles
with the line straight across.

00:28:38.520 --> 00:28:41.780 align:middle line:84%
That has a lot of implications
for an aging population.

00:28:41.780 --> 00:28:45.910 align:middle line:84%
I had a birthday yesterday, and
so, you know, it's on my mind.

00:28:45.910 --> 00:28:48.290 align:middle line:84%
And there's always a little
more gray hair every year

00:28:48.290 --> 00:28:49.050 align:middle line:90%
in the mirror.

00:28:49.050 --> 00:28:51.030 align:middle line:84%
So anyway, use it
or lose it, right?

00:28:51.030 --> 00:28:54.170 align:middle line:84%
It applies to the brain as well
