That's pretty interesting--
streaming on by.

00:32:01.051 --> 00:32:01.550 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Ah.

00:32:01.550 --> 00:32:02.580 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: So that's one thing.

00:32:02.580 --> 00:32:04.371 align:middle line:84%
And then, if you want,
you can deliberately

00:32:04.371 --> 00:32:06.030 align:middle line:90%
cultivate certain qualities.

00:32:06.030 --> 00:32:08.990 align:middle line:84%
You can open to feelings
of compassion or loving

00:32:08.990 --> 00:32:11.805 align:middle line:84%
kindness for yourself
or other beings.

00:32:11.805 --> 00:32:16.370 align:middle line:84%
Or you can also open to a
growing tranquility, a growing

00:32:16.370 --> 00:32:17.780 align:middle line:90%
feeling of being centered.

00:32:17.780 --> 00:32:21.630 align:middle line:84%
And, as you register
these states of being,

00:32:21.630 --> 00:32:24.400 align:middle line:84%
you can also help them
install themselves

00:32:24.400 --> 00:32:28.121 align:middle line:84%
into your brain as wholesome
traits of being, as well.

00:32:28.121 --> 00:32:30.120 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, this has
to do with a conversation

00:32:30.120 --> 00:32:31.299 align:middle line:90%
about forgiveness, as well.

00:32:31.299 --> 00:32:31.840 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: OK.

00:32:31.840 --> 00:32:34.740 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Because when--
say you're in that moment

00:32:34.740 --> 00:32:37.020 align:middle line:84%
and you have a really
peaceful moment,

00:32:37.020 --> 00:32:40.550 align:middle line:84%
and then the next moment is
another very stressful moment.

00:32:40.550 --> 00:32:43.960 align:middle line:84%
Or somebody does
something wrong to you,

00:32:43.960 --> 00:32:47.890 align:middle line:84%
or the bank account
is still at zero.

00:32:47.890 --> 00:32:49.566 align:middle line:90%
You launch back into that.

00:32:49.566 --> 00:32:51.190 align:middle line:84%
So you're fine in
the meditative state,

00:32:51.190 --> 00:32:55.204 align:middle line:84%
but then you jump into the next
moment, and it's not so pretty.

00:32:55.204 --> 00:32:55.870 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Right.

00:32:55.870 --> 00:32:57.660 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So how do
you carry that over?

00:32:57.660 --> 00:32:58.180 align:middle line:90%
I mean--

00:32:58.180 --> 00:32:59.210 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: You mean after
you're done meditating

00:32:59.210 --> 00:33:00.640 align:middle line:90%
or while you're in a meditation?

00:33:00.640 --> 00:33:01.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: No.

00:33:01.140 --> 00:33:03.213 align:middle line:84%
After you're done
meditating, how

00:33:03.213 --> 00:33:04.780 align:middle line:90%
do you deal with chronic stress?

00:33:04.780 --> 00:33:05.580 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Oh, yeah.

00:33:05.580 --> 00:33:11.430 align:middle line:84%
So people can, I think, sort
of mystify and meditation.

00:33:11.430 --> 00:33:13.250 align:middle line:84%
But in a lot of ways,
it really boils down

00:33:13.250 --> 00:33:14.620 align:middle line:90%
to it's a kind of training.

00:33:14.620 --> 00:33:16.920 align:middle line:84%
And like any sort
of training-- to use

00:33:16.920 --> 00:33:20.160 align:middle line:84%
a really technical term in
neuropsychology-- "Mo Better."

00:33:20.160 --> 00:33:24.260 align:middle line:84%
In other words, more
episodes, more times

00:33:24.260 --> 00:33:27.260 align:middle line:84%
in which you're actually
engaging your training--

00:33:27.260 --> 00:33:28.820 align:middle line:84%
meditating every
day, for example,

00:33:28.820 --> 00:33:31.410 align:middle line:84%
or doing yoga every day, or
walking the dog peacefully

00:33:31.410 --> 00:33:34.950 align:middle line:84%
every day, or doing Pilates
very mindfully every day,

00:33:34.950 --> 00:33:36.770 align:middle line:90%
or knitting or doing handwork.

00:33:36.770 --> 00:33:38.780 align:middle line:84%
Brushing your daughter's
hair every day.

00:33:38.780 --> 00:33:41.470 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Walking
meditation from you.

00:33:41.470 --> 00:33:42.587 align:middle line:90%
I do that all the time.

00:33:42.587 --> 00:33:43.212 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:33:43.212 --> 00:33:43.380 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:33:43.380 --> 00:33:44.730 align:middle line:90%
So "Mo Better" in that sense.

00:33:44.730 --> 00:33:47.930 align:middle line:84%
And then, second, inside
those episodes of practice,

00:33:47.930 --> 00:33:50.690 align:middle line:84%
whatever they happen to
be for you that fit you,

00:33:50.690 --> 00:33:52.110 align:middle line:90%
more depth of engagement.

00:33:52.110 --> 00:33:55.430 align:middle line:84%
And if you do that,
you will be creating

00:33:55.430 --> 00:33:57.200 align:middle line:84%
changes in neural
structure and function

00:33:57.200 --> 00:34:01.270 align:middle line:84%
that you'll then be able to
take with you, increasingly,

00:34:01.270 --> 00:34:03.940 align:middle line:84%
wherever you go out
there in daily life.

00:34:03.940 --> 00:34:05.807 align:middle line:84%
That's why I think it's
important to train,

00:34:05.807 --> 00:34:07.890 align:middle line:84%
to do these practices that
are wholesome, whatever

00:34:07.890 --> 00:34:09.290 align:middle line:84%
the ones that
appeal to a person,

00:34:09.290 --> 00:34:11.980 align:middle line:84%
and then steepen your
learning curve from them

00:34:11.980 --> 00:34:14.690 align:middle line:84%
so that increasingly-- and I
think you're exactly right.

00:34:14.690 --> 00:34:17.300 align:middle line:84%
We've all known people who
have good meditation practice,

00:34:17.300 --> 00:34:19.670 align:middle line:84%
and they're really neurotic
and a pain in the neck

00:34:19.670 --> 00:34:21.969 align:middle line:84%
to live with, work
with, or sleep with,

00:34:21.969 --> 00:34:22.960 align:middle line:90%
or all of the above.

00:34:22.960 --> 00:34:23.560 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:34:23.560 --> 00:34:24.590 align:middle line:90%
And, no.

00:34:24.590 --> 00:34:27.616 align:middle line:84%
You want to be able to engage
the challenges of life.

00:34:27.616 --> 00:34:29.532 align:middle line:84%
There's a joke saying
in the monastery-- think

00:34:29.532 --> 00:34:30.689 align:middle line:90%
you're so enlightened?

00:34:30.689 --> 00:34:31.730 align:middle line:90%
Go home for the holidays.

00:34:31.730 --> 00:34:32.485 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:34:32.485 --> 00:34:33.130 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:34:33.130 --> 00:34:33.659 align:middle line:90%
Tell your family what you do.

00:34:33.659 --> 00:34:35.242 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: You want
to be able to yeah.

00:34:35.242 --> 00:34:37.961 align:middle line:84%
I think of it as like
a sailboat with a keel.

00:34:37.961 --> 00:34:38.460 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:34:38.460 --> 00:34:42.300 align:middle line:84%
And I sailed once as a beginner
with a boat that had no keel,

00:34:42.300 --> 00:34:43.540 align:middle line:90%
and I capsized it.

00:34:43.540 --> 00:34:46.290 align:middle line:90%
We want a keel in our sailboat.

00:34:46.290 --> 00:34:47.969 align:middle line:84%
As we do our
practices-- including

00:34:47.969 --> 00:34:51.429 align:middle line:84%
by just watching your program,
for example, and letting it

00:34:51.429 --> 00:34:54.280 align:middle line:84%
sink in-- steepening
your learning curve

00:34:54.280 --> 00:34:56.070 align:middle line:90%
from Gaiam TV, et cetera.

00:34:56.070 --> 00:34:59.540 align:middle line:84%
As you do that, you deepen
this keel of your sailboat.

00:34:59.540 --> 00:35:01.870 align:middle line:84%
And research is beginning
to show you're actually

00:35:01.870 --> 00:35:03.720 align:middle line:84%
changing the structure
of your brain.

00:35:03.720 --> 00:35:06.520 align:middle line:84%
And as you do that-- as you
become more resourced inside,

00:35:06.520 --> 00:35:08.670 align:middle line:84%
as you become more trained
through repetition,

00:35:08.670 --> 00:35:13.630 align:middle line:84%
as more of these good things
get installed inside you,

00:35:13.630 --> 00:35:15.750 align:middle line:90%
your keel gets deeper.

00:35:15.750 --> 00:35:18.900 align:middle line:84%
You can afford to go out
and sail the deep dark blue.

00:35:18.900 --> 00:35:21.240 align:middle line:84%
The storms don't knock
you over so much.

00:35:21.240 --> 00:35:23.650 align:middle line:90%
You can risk greater things.

00:35:23.650 --> 00:35:25.309 align:middle line:90%
You can dream bigger dreams.

00:35:25.309 --> 00:35:26.850 align:middle line:84%
And if you do get
banged hard, you're

00:35:26.850 --> 00:35:28.480 align:middle line:84%
going to recover a
lot more quickly.

00:35:28.480 --> 00:35:29.910 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:35:29.910 --> 00:35:32.021 align:middle line:84%
That's a great
metaphor, as well.

00:35:32.021 --> 00:35:32.520 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:35:32.520 --> 00:35:34.330 align:middle line:84%
We're going to take a
look at another clip

00:35:34.330 --> 00:35:37.380 align:middle line:84%
here of you talking about the
different levels of the brain.

00:35:37.380 --> 00:35:39.260 align:middle line:90%
Take a look at this.

00:35:39.260 --> 00:35:43.290 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: What happens if
we feel over-challenged

00:35:43.290 --> 00:35:47.320 align:middle line:84%
and we're not able to experience
being fundamentally safe,

00:35:47.320 --> 00:35:48.950 align:middle line:84%
even if we're dealing
with challenges

00:35:48.950 --> 00:35:50.600 align:middle line:90%
or threats or danger?

00:35:50.600 --> 00:35:55.420 align:middle line:84%
We are not able to feel
fundamentally satisfied

00:35:55.420 --> 00:35:59.320 align:middle line:84%
if we're dealing with losses
or opportunities just out

00:35:59.320 --> 00:36:00.030 align:middle line:90%
of reach.

00:36:00.030 --> 00:36:05.070 align:middle line:84%
And we're not able, let's say,
to feel fundamentally loved

00:36:05.070 --> 00:36:08.940 align:middle line:84%
even as we grapple with issues
in the relationship field.

00:36:08.940 --> 00:36:11.520 align:middle line:84%
Then the brain has
a second setting.

00:36:11.520 --> 00:36:14.390 align:middle line:84%
It moves out of the green zone,
which I call the responsive

00:36:14.390 --> 00:36:17.790 align:middle line:84%
mode of the brain, and it
tips into the fight or flight

00:36:17.790 --> 00:36:20.950 align:middle line:84%
red zone, the reactive
mode of the brain--

00:36:20.950 --> 00:36:22.550 align:middle line:90%
two settings of the brain.

00:36:22.550 --> 00:36:26.560 align:middle line:84%
And in that state, in terms
of the avoiding harm system,

00:36:26.560 --> 00:36:29.810 align:middle line:84%
we tip into a state
of fear-- flight.

00:36:29.810 --> 00:36:33.650 align:middle line:84%
We want to withdraw from what's
unpleasant, or resist it.

00:36:33.650 --> 00:36:36.280 align:middle line:84%
Or, in terms of the
reward-seeking part

00:36:36.280 --> 00:36:38.670 align:middle line:84%
of the brain, the carrot-seeking
part of the brain,

00:36:38.670 --> 00:36:42.290 align:middle line:84%
we tip into a state of
frustration, driveness,

00:36:42.290 --> 00:36:44.330 align:middle line:90%
and grasping, if you will.

00:36:44.330 --> 00:36:48.560 align:middle line:84%
And in terms of the attaching
to others system of the brain,

00:36:48.560 --> 00:36:51.990 align:middle line:84%
when we experience that those
basic needs for connection

00:36:51.990 --> 00:36:55.430 align:middle line:84%
are not met, we tip into
a state of envy or shame

00:36:55.430 --> 00:36:59.600 align:middle line:84%
or loneliness or, in
a word, heartache.

00:36:59.600 --> 00:37:01.940 align:middle line:84%
This is the brain
in the red zone.

00:37:01.940 --> 00:37:03.780 align:middle line:90%
The body kicks into gear.

00:37:03.780 --> 00:37:06.140 align:middle line:84%
The stress hormones
flood through us,

00:37:06.140 --> 00:37:08.400 align:middle line:84%
including moving back
up into the brain,

00:37:08.400 --> 00:37:14.070 align:middle line:84%
and we run from the lion or
we chase the opportunity or we

00:37:14.070 --> 00:37:17.910 align:middle line:84%
struggle with or
cling to others.

00:37:17.910 --> 00:37:20.990 align:middle line:84%
Bodily resources are burned
faster than we can take them

00:37:20.990 --> 00:37:23.930 align:middle line:84%
in, long-term projects
are put on hold,

00:37:23.930 --> 00:37:26.210 align:middle line:84%
and the mind, in
three basic words,

00:37:26.210 --> 00:37:29.410 align:middle line:84%
is colored by a state of fear,
frustration, and heartache--

00:37:29.410 --> 00:37:33.227 align:middle line:84%
in terms of those three
core systems and core needs.

00:37:33.227 --> 00:37:34.810 align:middle line:84%
That's a brain that's
colored strongly

00:37:34.810 --> 00:37:36.890 align:middle line:84%
by qualities of
resisting, in terms

00:37:36.890 --> 00:37:40.400 align:middle line:84%
of the avoiding system,
qualities of grasping,

00:37:40.400 --> 00:37:43.100 align:middle line:84%
in terms of the approach
and reward system,

00:37:43.100 --> 00:37:45.630 align:middle line:84%
and a quality of
clinging in terms

00:37:45.630 --> 00:37:47.910 align:middle line:84%
of the attaching
to others system.

00:37:47.910 --> 00:37:49.740 align:middle line:84%
Or, in a single
encompassing word,

00:37:49.740 --> 00:37:54.520 align:middle line:84%
a brain colored by craving
and therefore suffering.

00:37:54.520 --> 00:37:56.830 align:middle line:84%
So for those of you who are
tracking what I'm doing,

00:37:56.830 --> 00:37:59.020 align:middle line:84%
I'm trying to
naturalize the dharma.

00:37:59.020 --> 00:38:02.510 align:middle line:84%
In other words, I'm trying to
ground this ancient Buddhist

00:38:02.510 --> 00:38:04.760 align:middle line:84%
psychology that's
profoundly penetrating

00:38:04.760 --> 00:38:07.510 align:middle line:84%
in its analysis of
human psychology

00:38:07.510 --> 00:38:10.135 align:middle line:84%
without reference, in the
frame that I'm working in,

00:38:10.135 --> 00:38:14.490 align:middle line:84%
to anything supernatural or
metaphysical or transcendental.

00:38:14.490 --> 00:38:16.570 align:middle line:84%
In that frame, the
Buddha's analysis,

00:38:16.570 --> 00:38:18.990 align:middle line:84%
of course, as you know,
is that forms of craving

00:38:18.990 --> 00:38:20.430 align:middle line:90%
lead to suffering.

00:38:20.430 --> 00:38:24.580 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So how does one get out
of the red zone of the brain?

00:38:24.580 --> 00:38:25.710 align:middle line:90%
We left it off there.

00:38:25.710 --> 00:38:26.644 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: All right.

00:38:26.644 --> 00:38:28.685 align:middle line:84%
Well, so I'll have to give
a little explanation--

00:38:28.685 --> 00:38:28.980 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:38:28.980 --> 00:38:29.112 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: OK.

00:38:29.112 --> 00:38:29.612 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:38:29.612 --> 00:38:32.680 align:middle line:84%
So a way to think about it
is that the brain evolved

00:38:32.680 --> 00:38:35.550 align:middle line:84%
in three stages, which I
summarize as lizard, mouse,

00:38:35.550 --> 00:38:38.530 align:middle line:84%
and monkey-- brain
stem, subcortex, cortex.

00:38:38.530 --> 00:38:41.482 align:middle line:84%
That's a super simple
summary of a lot of material,

00:38:41.482 --> 00:38:43.940 align:middle line:84%
so I don't want to freak out
the neuroscientists out there.

00:38:43.940 --> 00:38:44.040 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:38:44.040 --> 00:38:45.873 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: But anyway,
it's a useful summary.

00:38:45.873 --> 00:38:47.950 align:middle line:84%
And as our ancestors
evolved, they

00:38:47.950 --> 00:38:51.390 align:middle line:84%
had to solve survival problems
related to our three core

00:38:51.390 --> 00:38:55.670 align:middle line:84%
needs-- safety,
satisfaction, and connection.

00:38:55.670 --> 00:38:58.260 align:middle line:84%
And obviously as the
brain has evolved,

00:38:58.260 --> 00:38:59.960 align:middle line:84%
we've gotten better
and better at that.

00:38:59.960 --> 00:39:00.880 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:39:00.880 --> 00:39:03.760 align:middle line:84%
Well, what happens when
you don't feel safe

00:39:03.760 --> 00:39:07.160 align:middle line:84%
or you don't feel
satisfied, broadly speaking,

00:39:07.160 --> 00:39:09.800 align:middle line:84%
or you don't feel
connected or loved--

00:39:09.800 --> 00:39:11.650 align:middle line:84%
the brain goes into
the red zone, fight

00:39:11.650 --> 00:39:14.463 align:middle line:90%
or flight of reactivation.

00:39:14.463 --> 00:39:15.270 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Instantly.

00:39:15.270 --> 00:39:17.690 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Or brrp,
freeze response.

00:39:17.690 --> 00:39:22.350 align:middle line:84%
Either way, long-term projects
in the body are put on hold,

00:39:22.350 --> 00:39:26.200 align:middle line:84%
so the immune system gets
weaker, digestion goes down,

00:39:26.200 --> 00:39:27.900 align:middle line:90%
hormones get very disturbed.

00:39:27.900 --> 00:39:31.330 align:middle line:84%
And the mind, in terms
of the three broad needs

00:39:31.330 --> 00:39:34.100 align:middle line:84%
I'm describing-- safety,
satisfaction, and connection--

00:39:34.100 --> 00:39:38.230 align:middle line:84%
is colored with a sense of
fear, frustration, or heartache,

00:39:38.230 --> 00:39:40.950 align:middle line:90%
in three broad umbrella terms.

00:39:40.950 --> 00:39:42.840 align:middle line:90%
That's the red zone.

00:39:42.840 --> 00:39:45.490 align:middle line:84%
The good news is
that in our bodies,

00:39:45.490 --> 00:39:48.960 align:middle line:84%
Mother Nature has evolved
as well the green zone.

00:39:48.960 --> 00:39:51.940 align:middle line:84%
When we experience in
our core that we're

00:39:51.940 --> 00:39:54.540 align:middle line:84%
fundamentally safe,
fundamentally satisfied,

00:39:54.540 --> 00:39:57.140 align:middle line:84%
and fundamentally
connected and loved,

00:39:57.140 --> 00:40:01.020 align:middle line:84%
then we default to our resting
state, this sustainable

00:40:01.020 --> 00:40:04.840 align:middle line:84%
equilibrium condition in which
the body repairs and refuels

00:40:04.840 --> 00:40:05.620 align:middle line:90%
itself.

00:40:05.620 --> 00:40:07.799 align:middle line:84%
It recovers from
bursts of stress.

00:40:07.799 --> 00:40:10.215 align:middle line:84%
And, in terms of those three
needs-- safety, satisfaction,

00:40:10.215 --> 00:40:12.340 align:middle line:84%
and connection--
the mind is colored

00:40:12.340 --> 00:40:16.540 align:middle line:84%
with a sense of peace,
contentment, and love, in three

00:40:16.540 --> 00:40:17.830 align:middle line:90%
broad umbrella terms.

00:40:17.830 --> 00:40:20.040 align:middle line:84%
So much of what life's
about-- as well as

00:40:20.040 --> 00:40:22.590 align:middle line:84%
to use the example
Buddhist practice--

00:40:22.590 --> 00:40:25.160 align:middle line:84%
is about getting
out of the red zone

00:40:25.160 --> 00:40:27.660 align:middle line:84%
and resting increasingly
in the green zone

00:40:27.660 --> 00:40:31.610 align:middle line:84%
even as we deal with the
challenges of life, of being

00:40:31.610 --> 00:40:35.830 align:middle line:84%
busy, raising a family,
having a career, being on TV.

00:40:35.830 --> 00:40:37.540 align:middle line:84%
Even as we deal with
real challenges,

00:40:37.540 --> 00:40:40.290 align:middle line:84%
we can stay green
as we engage them.

00:40:40.290 --> 00:40:42.530 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Is that like
the relaxation response

00:40:42.530 --> 00:40:43.752 align:middle line:90%
or is it different?

00:40:43.752 --> 00:40:45.460 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: I think the
relaxation response

00:40:45.460 --> 00:40:47.980 align:middle line:84%
is a great resource,
speaking of that,

00:40:47.980 --> 00:40:49.356 align:middle line:84%
especially for
the safety system.

00:40:49.356 --> 00:40:49.980 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, OK.

00:40:49.980 --> 00:40:51.410 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Because
as we relax, we

00:40:51.410 --> 00:40:54.010 align:middle line:84%
feel less threatened
and more stable.

00:40:54.010 --> 00:40:55.740 align:middle line:84%
If you think about
it, relaxation

00:40:55.740 --> 00:40:57.782 align:middle line:84%
is the opposite of fight
or flight-- or freezing.

00:40:57.782 --> 00:40:59.864 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And it usually
comes after fight or flight

00:40:59.864 --> 00:41:00.476 align:middle line:90%
though, right?

00:41:00.476 --> 00:41:01.100 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:41:01.100 --> 00:41:03.210 align:middle line:84%
A lot of what life's about
is how do you get out

00:41:03.210 --> 00:41:06.130 align:middle line:84%
of the red zone as fast
as possible, and second,

00:41:06.130 --> 00:41:08.670 align:middle line:84%
how do you stabilize
in the green zone

00:41:08.670 --> 00:41:12.060 align:middle line:84%
and deepen the keel
of your green zone,

00:41:12.060 --> 00:41:15.765 align:middle line:84%
deeper and deeper, so you
can stay green even when

00:41:15.765 --> 00:41:17.750 align:middle line:84%
the oatmeal starts
to fly around you.

00:41:17.750 --> 00:41:19.940 align:middle line:84%
And that's why taking
in the good-- as I

00:41:19.940 --> 00:41:22.130 align:middle line:84%
talk about in my book--
many times a day,

00:41:22.130 --> 00:41:25.210 align:middle line:84%
half a dozen times a day, less
than half a minute at a time,

00:41:25.210 --> 00:41:26.460 align:middle line:90%
is a reasonable expectation.

00:41:26.460 --> 00:41:28.310 align:middle line:84%
That's less than
five minutes a day.

00:41:28.310 --> 00:41:29.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And taking in the good.

00:41:29.690 --> 00:41:29.950 align:middle line:90%
What is that?

00:41:29.950 --> 00:41:31.195 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Staying with
that useful experience.

00:41:31.195 --> 00:41:31.500 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:41:31.500 --> 00:41:32.710 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: So when you're
in the green zone,

00:41:32.710 --> 00:41:35.043 align:middle line:84%
or having a taste of it, when
you're having a relaxation

00:41:35.043 --> 00:41:37.500 align:middle line:84%
response, when you're
feeling satisfied,

00:41:37.500 --> 00:41:39.470 align:middle line:84%
a wholesome pleasure,
you're drinking water

00:41:39.470 --> 00:41:40.450 align:middle line:90%
when you're thirsty.

00:41:40.450 --> 00:41:40.930 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You have a break.

00:41:40.930 --> 00:41:41.220 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:41:41.220 --> 00:41:41.840 align:middle line:90%
You have a break.

00:41:41.840 --> 00:41:42.340 align:middle line:90%
Whew.

00:41:42.340 --> 00:41:46.070 align:middle line:84%
Or you accomplish something, or
you're just enjoying yourself,

00:41:46.070 --> 00:41:47.800 align:middle line:84%
or you're feeling
grateful or glad.

00:41:47.800 --> 00:41:49.350 align:middle line:90%
That's the satisfaction system.

00:41:49.350 --> 00:41:49.850 align:middle line:90%
All right?

00:41:49.850 --> 00:41:50.700 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:41:50.700 --> 00:41:53.990 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Or if you feel
appreciated or included or seen

00:41:53.990 --> 00:41:54.900 align:middle line:90%
or liked or loved.

00:41:54.900 --> 00:41:56.441 align:middle line:84%
When you're having
these experiences,

00:41:56.441 --> 00:41:59.670 align:middle line:84%
like we were saying earlier,
don't waste them on your brain.

00:41:59.670 --> 00:42:01.750 align:middle line:84%
Stay with them
five, 10, 20 seconds

00:42:01.750 --> 00:42:04.730 align:middle line:84%
in a row to really hardwire
that happiness in you

00:42:04.730 --> 00:42:10.404 align:middle line:84%
and deepen the keel, the green
keel, of your sailboat one

00:42:10.404 --> 00:42:12.820 align:middle line:84%
synapse at the time, as it
were-- these little connections

00:42:12.820 --> 00:42:13.790 align:middle line:90%
between neurons.

00:42:13.790 --> 00:42:15.400 align:middle line:84%
To me, that's a
fantastic practice.

00:42:15.400 --> 00:42:18.600 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So more and more of
that is taking in the good,

00:42:18.600 --> 00:42:20.690 align:middle line:90%
and that builds the brain.

00:42:20.690 --> 00:42:23.452 align:middle line:84%
It built in the brain
the happiness factor.

00:42:23.452 --> 00:42:24.410 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: That's right.

00:42:24.410 --> 00:42:27.710 align:middle line:84%
It builds in your brain an
increasingly unconditional

00:42:27.710 --> 00:42:28.349 align:middle line:90%
inner peace.

00:42:28.349 --> 00:42:30.265 align:middle line:84%
So even when you're
threatened or challenged--

00:42:30.265 --> 00:42:30.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Nice.

00:42:30.820 --> 00:42:33.250 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: --you can stay
calm and centered and strong

00:42:33.250 --> 00:42:34.010 align:middle line:90%
inside yourself.

00:42:34.010 --> 00:42:36.510 align:middle line:84%
You start weaving into
your brain more and more

00:42:36.510 --> 00:42:38.050 align:middle line:90%
an unconditional contentment.

00:42:38.050 --> 00:42:41.530 align:middle line:84%
So even if there's loss around
you or you're obstructed,

00:42:41.530 --> 00:42:44.620 align:middle line:84%
you feel more and more
like you're already full.

00:42:44.620 --> 00:42:48.140 align:middle line:84%
And third, as you internalize,
again and again and again,

00:42:48.140 --> 00:42:49.930 align:middle line:84%
little moments that
are authentic-- we're

00:42:49.930 --> 00:42:51.230 align:middle line:90%
not making anything up here.

00:42:51.230 --> 00:42:52.870 align:middle line:84%
This is not looking
on the bright side.

00:42:52.870 --> 00:42:54.350 align:middle line:90%
This is seeing what's true.

00:42:54.350 --> 00:42:56.010 align:middle line:90%
There is attention here.

00:42:56.010 --> 00:42:57.190 align:middle line:90%
There is caring here.

00:42:57.190 --> 00:42:58.485 align:middle line:90%
There is respect here.

00:42:58.485 --> 00:42:59.387 align:middle line:90%
There is liking here.

00:42:59.387 --> 00:42:59.970 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:42:59.970 --> 00:43:00.260 align:middle line:90%
Take a look at that.

00:43:00.260 --> 00:43:00.885 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Good.

00:43:00.885 --> 00:43:02.829 align:middle line:84%
I have an opportunity
to actually feel that.

00:43:02.829 --> 00:43:04.620 align:middle line:84%
If we do that again
and again and again, we

00:43:04.620 --> 00:43:07.990 align:middle line:84%
build those strengths inside
so that we can stay green

00:43:07.990 --> 00:43:10.860 align:middle line:84%
as the challenges in
our life actually grow.

00:43:10.860 --> 00:43:14.380 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's a fantastic
practice because, in part, it's

00:43:14.380 --> 00:43:16.010 align:middle line:90%
usually enjoyable.

00:43:16.010 --> 00:43:17.641 align:middle line:90%
The green zone feels good.

00:43:17.641 --> 00:43:18.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:43:18.140 --> 00:43:21.100 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: The more that we
deeply register the green zone

00:43:21.100 --> 00:43:25.150 align:middle line:84%
and we value it and come
home to it again and again,

00:43:25.150 --> 00:43:27.270 align:middle line:84%
the more it's going to
sink in, the more it's

00:43:27.270 --> 00:43:30.310 align:middle line:84%
going to weave itself into the
fabric of our brain and, thus,

00:43:30.310 --> 00:43:31.464 align:middle line:90%
our life.

00:43:31.464 --> 00:43:33.880 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So is that what you
talk about in "The Neurodharma

00:43:33.880 --> 00:43:34.570 align:middle line:90%
of Love?"

00:43:34.570 --> 00:43:35.280 align:middle line:90%
And what is that?

00:43:35.280 --> 00:43:38.410 align:middle line:84%
I love that name-- "The
Neurodharma of Love."

00:43:38.410 --> 00:43:39.650 align:middle line:90%
What is neurodharma?

00:43:39.650 --> 00:43:41.900 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Well, for me,
neurodharma is a made-up term.

00:43:41.900 --> 00:43:43.608 align:middle line:84%
I don't think it'll
ever get me on Oprah.

00:43:43.608 --> 00:43:46.040 align:middle line:84%
But anyway, I like it
a lot-- geek that I am.

00:43:46.040 --> 00:43:48.610 align:middle line:84%
It puts together
the idea of thinking

00:43:48.610 --> 00:43:53.410 align:middle line:84%
about what are the underlying
causes and conditions in life

00:43:53.410 --> 00:43:57.030 align:middle line:84%
itself, in our
own animal nature,

00:43:57.030 --> 00:43:59.880 align:middle line:84%
coming in to an intimacy
with our own body?

00:43:59.880 --> 00:44:01.420 align:middle line:84%
What are the causes
and conditions

00:44:01.420 --> 00:44:06.729 align:middle line:84%
to be found there of profound
inner peace, wisdom, and love?

00:44:06.729 --> 00:44:08.770 align:middle line:84%
That's, to me, the territory
of the neurodharma--

00:44:08.770 --> 00:44:11.970 align:middle line:84%
the intersection of
modern neuropsychology

00:44:11.970 --> 00:44:15.190 align:middle line:84%
and the ancient wisdom
originating over

00:44:15.190 --> 00:44:18.120 align:middle line:84%
25,000 years ago in
the Buddhist dream

00:44:18.120 --> 00:44:19.759 align:middle line:84%
that's come all the
way to us today.

00:44:19.759 --> 00:44:21.800 align:middle line:84%
I think that's a really
interesting intersection,

00:44:21.800 --> 00:44:22.930 align:middle line:90%
again, of two circles.

00:44:22.930 --> 00:44:26.310 align:middle line:84%
And what I did is I applied
that to relationships,

00:44:26.310 --> 00:44:28.390 align:middle line:90%
including messy relationships.

00:44:28.390 --> 00:44:31.361 align:middle line:84%
It's easy to be loving and super
chill when you're partner's

00:44:31.361 --> 00:44:32.860 align:middle line:84%
just giving you
everything you want.

00:44:32.860 --> 00:44:33.050 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:44:33.050 --> 00:44:34.320 align:middle line:84%
But then there's
financial issues,

00:44:34.320 --> 00:44:35.310 align:middle line:90%
and all of those things--

00:44:35.310 --> 00:44:35.670 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:44:35.670 --> 00:44:37.753 align:middle line:84%
Differences of opinion
about how to raise the kids

00:44:37.753 --> 00:44:39.770 align:middle line:84%
or live life together,
or busy schedules,

00:44:39.770 --> 00:44:41.030 align:middle line:90%
or misunderstandings.

00:44:41.030 --> 00:44:41.850 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:44:41.850 --> 00:44:43.100 align:middle line:90%
Taking each other for granted.

00:44:43.100 --> 00:44:44.350 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Taking each
other for granted

00:44:44.350 --> 00:44:45.391 align:middle line:90%
and all the rest of that.

00:44:45.391 --> 00:44:48.040 align:middle line:84%
So what that program's
about is the idea

00:44:48.040 --> 00:44:51.740 align:middle line:84%
of applying this incredible
toolbox from the Buddha

00:44:51.740 --> 00:44:55.080 align:middle line:84%
as well as the modern
toolbox from neuropsychology

00:44:55.080 --> 00:44:58.060 align:middle line:84%
and looking at the best
of both of those, applied

00:44:58.060 --> 00:45:01.555 align:middle line:84%
into relationships in
very, very practical ways.

00:45:01.555 --> 00:45:03.180 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's
incredibly important

00:45:03.180 --> 00:45:05.910 align:middle line:84%
because, as you said at the
very beginning, most of our joys

00:45:05.910 --> 00:45:08.820 align:middle line:84%
and most of our sorrows
happen in relationships.

00:45:08.820 --> 00:45:10.781 align:middle line:84%
We're the most social
species on the planet.

00:45:10.781 --> 00:45:11.280 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:45:11.280 --> 00:45:11.900 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:45:11.900 --> 00:45:15.350 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: And as I find that,
as people feel-- a lot of people

00:45:15.350 --> 00:45:19.430 align:middle line:84%
feel like they're running on
empty and they're rattled.

00:45:19.430 --> 00:45:21.121 align:middle line:84%
They're being banged
on all day long.

00:45:21.121 --> 00:45:22.870 align:middle line:84%
So there's an internal
sense, if you will,

00:45:22.870 --> 00:45:24.540 align:middle line:90%
of deficit and disturbance.

00:45:24.540 --> 00:45:28.785 align:middle line:84%
And that's the underlying cause
of the red zone-- an underlying

00:45:28.785 --> 00:45:30.350 align:middle line:84%
sense of deficit
and disturbance.

00:45:30.350 --> 00:45:30.850 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:45:30.850 --> 00:45:30.920 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:45:30.920 --> 00:45:33.440 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: So if you repeatedly
feed yourself and you feed

00:45:33.440 --> 00:45:36.910 align:middle line:84%
your heart, you gradually
undo that underlying sense

00:45:36.910 --> 00:45:37.860 align:middle line:90%
of deficit.

00:45:37.860 --> 00:45:40.910 align:middle line:84%
And as you gradually internalize
regulation and balance

00:45:40.910 --> 00:45:43.930 align:middle line:84%
and equanimity and ease, even as
you're dealing with real life.

00:45:43.930 --> 00:45:45.480 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes equanimity
is described

00:45:45.480 --> 00:45:48.136 align:middle line:84%
as walking evenly
over uneven ground.

00:45:48.136 --> 00:45:48.636 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh.

00:45:48.636 --> 00:45:48.700 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:45:48.700 --> 00:45:49.230 align:middle line:90%
That makes sense.

00:45:49.230 --> 00:45:49.645 align:middle line:90%
That's a good visual.

00:45:49.645 --> 00:45:49.900 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:45:49.900 --> 00:45:50.620 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:45:50.620 --> 00:45:52.640 align:middle line:84%
As you repeatedly
internalize that,

00:45:52.640 --> 00:45:56.200 align:middle line:84%
you become more and more
able to be really loving

00:45:56.200 --> 00:45:59.420 align:middle line:84%
in relationships as
well as really strong.

00:45:59.420 --> 00:46:01.430 align:middle line:84%
It's relatively
straightforward to be loving.

00:46:01.430 --> 00:46:03.560 align:middle line:84%
It's relatively
straightforward to be strong.

00:46:03.560 --> 00:46:05.840 align:middle line:90%
But to be loving and strong--

00:46:05.840 --> 00:46:08.220 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Can both people be
that in the relationship?

00:46:08.220 --> 00:46:08.830 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yes.

00:46:08.830 --> 00:46:09.890 align:middle line:90%
You have to respect each other.

00:46:09.890 --> 00:46:12.420 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's a wonderful
image of a relationship-- two

00:46:12.420 --> 00:46:13.465 align:middle line:90%
loving, strong people.

00:46:13.465 --> 00:46:13.611 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:46:13.611 --> 00:46:14.190 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:46:14.190 --> 00:46:14.790 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Very wonderful.

00:46:14.790 --> 00:46:15.289 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:46:15.289 --> 00:46:16.900 align:middle line:84%
Let's take a look
at more suggestions

00:46:16.900 --> 00:46:18.358 align:middle line:84%
that Rick Hanson
has in this video.

00:46:18.358 --> 00:46:19.890 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

00:46:19.890 --> 00:46:22.200 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: What to do, right?

00:46:22.200 --> 00:46:24.590 align:middle line:84%
Well, you can intervene
at lots of levels.

00:46:24.590 --> 00:46:26.330 align:middle line:90%
I'm like a methods guy.

00:46:26.330 --> 00:46:27.020 align:middle line:90%
I'm a brain guy.

00:46:27.020 --> 00:46:29.103 align:middle line:84%
So I intervene in terms
of the mind and the brain.

00:46:29.103 --> 00:46:29.970 align:middle line:90%
What can you do?

00:46:29.970 --> 00:46:34.140 align:middle line:84%
Number one-- get out of reactive
episodes as fast as you can.

00:46:34.140 --> 00:46:36.500 align:middle line:84%
Get out of the red zone
as quick as you can.

00:46:36.500 --> 00:46:38.270 align:middle line:84%
Because your brain
is over-learning

00:46:38.270 --> 00:46:39.910 align:middle line:90%
from the red zone.

00:46:39.910 --> 00:46:43.380 align:middle line:84%
Every red zone episode
makes you one smidge, if not

00:46:43.380 --> 00:46:48.020 align:middle line:84%
10 smidges, more vulnerable
to a reactive fight or flight,

00:46:48.020 --> 00:46:54.300 align:middle line:84%
stressful, fear, frustration,
and heartache experience.

00:46:54.300 --> 00:46:56.820 align:middle line:84%
Get out of the red zone
as fast as you can.

00:46:56.820 --> 00:46:59.040 align:middle line:84%
Second, do what you
can outside yourself

00:46:59.040 --> 00:47:01.480 align:middle line:90%
to prevent red zone experiences.

00:47:01.480 --> 00:47:01.980 align:middle line:90%
You know?

00:47:01.980 --> 00:47:03.180 align:middle line:90%
Do what you can.

00:47:03.180 --> 00:47:04.540 align:middle line:90%
Think about schedule.

00:47:04.540 --> 00:47:06.595 align:middle line:84%
Think about not adding
too many commitments.

00:47:06.595 --> 00:47:07.970 align:middle line:84%
I should think
about that myself.

00:47:07.970 --> 00:47:10.754 align:middle line:90%


00:47:10.754 --> 00:47:12.420 align:middle line:84%
Think about doing
what you can to create

00:47:12.420 --> 00:47:14.000 align:middle line:90%
more safety in your world.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:15.220 align:middle line:90%
We do what we can.

00:47:15.220 --> 00:47:16.010 align:middle line:90%
All right?

00:47:16.010 --> 00:47:18.200 align:middle line:84%
Third, and perhaps
most important of all--

00:47:18.200 --> 00:47:20.150 align:middle line:84%
which will be my segue
into the practice

00:47:20.150 --> 00:47:24.770 align:middle line:84%
to do with you momentarily-- is
to, again and again and again,

00:47:24.770 --> 00:47:28.060 align:middle line:84%
help this vulnerable
Stone Age brain,

00:47:28.060 --> 00:47:30.330 align:middle line:84%
which is really
older than Stone Age.

00:47:30.330 --> 00:47:33.040 align:middle line:84%
The nervous system is
600 million years old.

00:47:33.040 --> 00:47:33.970 align:middle line:90%
You know?

00:47:33.970 --> 00:47:37.270 align:middle line:84%
Each of us has within us
a kind of inner lizard,

00:47:37.270 --> 00:47:41.460 align:middle line:84%
inner mouse, and inner
monkey loosely associated

00:47:41.460 --> 00:47:42.960 align:middle line:84%
with the three
layers of the brain.

00:47:42.960 --> 00:47:46.680 align:middle line:84%
So very loosely, that lizard
needs a lot of petting.

00:47:46.680 --> 00:47:49.010 align:middle line:84%
You're safe, little
lizard buddy.

00:47:49.010 --> 00:47:50.410 align:middle line:90%
It's OK.

00:47:50.410 --> 00:47:53.150 align:middle line:84%
The little mouse
needs a lot of cheese.

00:47:53.150 --> 00:47:54.100 align:middle line:90%
You have enough.

00:47:54.100 --> 00:47:55.240 align:middle line:90%
It's OK.

00:47:55.240 --> 00:47:56.120 align:middle line:90%
You're full.

00:47:56.120 --> 00:47:57.340 align:middle line:90%
There's enough.

00:47:57.340 --> 00:48:01.240 align:middle line:84%
And the monkey needs
a lot of hugging.

00:48:01.240 --> 00:48:03.510 align:middle line:84%
And especially is what's
called neuroplasticity.

00:48:03.510 --> 00:48:05.180 align:middle line:84%
The capacity of
the brain to learn

00:48:05.180 --> 00:48:07.670 align:middle line:84%
goes down as you
move back in time.

00:48:07.670 --> 00:48:10.840 align:middle line:84%
That inner mouse, but
especially the inner lizard,

00:48:10.840 --> 00:48:13.720 align:middle line:84%
needs a lot of
soothing and petting.

00:48:13.720 --> 00:48:16.490 align:middle line:84%
We need a lot of
experiences of safety.

00:48:16.490 --> 00:48:20.480 align:middle line:84%
So the third way to deal with
this fundamental issue-- this

00:48:20.480 --> 00:48:23.660 align:middle line:84%
is a design feature in
evolution that I've described.

00:48:23.660 --> 00:48:26.750 align:middle line:84%
The three needs, the
two fundamental settings

00:48:26.750 --> 00:48:28.550 align:middle line:84%
of the brain-- that's
a design feature.

00:48:28.550 --> 00:48:30.800 align:middle line:84%
But in the 21st
century, in many ways,

00:48:30.800 --> 00:48:32.850 align:middle line:90%
it's a kind of design flaw.

00:48:32.850 --> 00:48:34.900 align:middle line:84%
It's like a bug in
the Stone Age brain.

00:48:34.900 --> 00:48:37.830 align:middle line:84%
So the third thing we
can do about it is,

00:48:37.830 --> 00:48:41.220 align:middle line:84%
again and again and again,
help it land inside.

00:48:41.220 --> 00:48:44.585 align:middle line:90%
10 seconds at a time-- safe.

00:48:44.585 --> 00:48:48.370 align:middle line:90%


00:48:48.370 --> 00:48:49.350 align:middle line:90%
Fed.

00:48:49.350 --> 00:48:51.070 align:middle line:90%
Enough.

00:48:51.070 --> 00:48:53.560 align:middle line:90%
Connected.

00:48:53.560 --> 00:48:54.990 align:middle line:90%
Part of.

00:48:54.990 --> 00:48:55.820 align:middle line:90%
Seen.

00:48:55.820 --> 00:48:57.000 align:middle line:90%
Liked.

00:48:57.000 --> 00:48:58.400 align:middle line:90%
Maybe loved.

00:48:58.400 --> 00:49:00.080 align:middle line:90%
Again and again and again.

00:49:00.080 --> 00:49:03.181 align:middle line:84%
And help this brain
take in the good.

00:49:03.181 --> 00:49:04.930 align:middle line:84%
In other words, again
and again and again,

00:49:04.930 --> 00:49:08.400 align:middle line:84%
roughly 10 seconds at a
time, help it really land.

00:49:08.400 --> 00:49:11.480 align:middle line:84%
Because negative learning
lands immediately.

00:49:11.480 --> 00:49:14.890 align:middle line:84%
The brain fast tracks negative
experiences into storage

00:49:14.890 --> 00:49:16.080 align:middle line:90%
right away.

00:49:16.080 --> 00:49:17.630 align:middle line:84%
Positive experiences,
unless they're

00:49:17.630 --> 00:49:20.480 align:middle line:84%
highly intense or novel,
million-dollar moments,

00:49:20.480 --> 00:49:23.640 align:middle line:84%
need to be held in awareness
past some loose threshold,

00:49:23.640 --> 00:49:26.755 align:middle line:84%
that's on the order of five,
10, 20 seconds, for them

00:49:26.755 --> 00:49:30.480 align:middle line:84%
to have a chance of transferring
from short-term memory buffers

00:49:30.480 --> 00:49:32.510 align:middle line:90%
down into long-term storage.

00:49:32.510 --> 00:49:36.760 align:middle line:84%
So we need to help
ourselves really register it

00:49:36.760 --> 00:49:39.620 align:middle line:84%
when our safety needs
are basically met,

00:49:39.620 --> 00:49:43.940 align:middle line:84%
when our reward-seeking or
satisfaction-seeking needs are

00:49:43.940 --> 00:49:45.770 align:middle line:84%
basically met,
and really help it

00:49:45.770 --> 00:49:48.200 align:middle line:84%
land when our needs
for connection

00:49:48.200 --> 00:49:51.110 align:middle line:84%
are basically met-- not
necessarily perfectly.

00:49:51.110 --> 00:49:55.460 align:middle line:84%
As Jean-Paul Sartre said,
hell is other people.

00:49:55.460 --> 00:49:55.960 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:49:55.960 --> 00:50:00.240 align:middle line:90%
So-- but basically met, OK?

00:50:00.240 --> 00:50:00.740 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:50:00.740 --> 00:50:03.090 align:middle line:84%
So we're bringing
joy and strength

00:50:03.090 --> 00:50:04.700 align:middle line:90%
and love into a relationship.

00:50:04.700 --> 00:50:06.830 align:middle line:90%
Let's talk about compassion.

00:50:06.830 --> 00:50:10.410 align:middle line:84%
And what are the neurochemical
benefits of compassion?

00:50:10.410 --> 00:50:11.802 align:middle line:90%
And this is great for all ages.

00:50:11.802 --> 00:50:12.760 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Oh, for sure.

00:50:12.760 --> 00:50:13.655 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:50:13.655 --> 00:50:15.350 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Compassion
is simply the wish

00:50:15.350 --> 00:50:17.820 align:middle line:84%
that a being not
suffer, usually combined

00:50:17.820 --> 00:50:20.700 align:middle line:84%
with a warm-hearted
sympathetic concern.

00:50:20.700 --> 00:50:23.590 align:middle line:84%
So it sounds kind of fancy,
but it's really simple.

00:50:23.590 --> 00:50:25.350 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What did you just say?

00:50:25.350 --> 00:50:26.230 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:50:26.230 --> 00:50:26.980 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Exactly.

00:50:26.980 --> 00:50:27.480 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:50:27.480 --> 00:50:29.060 align:middle line:84%
And there's actually
great research

00:50:29.060 --> 00:50:32.460 align:middle line:84%
the shows that one of the
main drivers of the evolution

00:50:32.460 --> 00:50:34.410 align:middle line:84%
of the human brain,
which has tripled

00:50:34.410 --> 00:50:37.290 align:middle line:84%
in its volume in the
last three million years.

00:50:37.290 --> 00:50:40.750 align:middle line:84%
One of the major drivers
of that is the benefits

00:50:40.750 --> 00:50:45.470 align:middle line:84%
of compassion and love in
mother-child relationships,

00:50:45.470 --> 00:50:48.290 align:middle line:84%
and then mother-partner
relationships, and then

00:50:48.290 --> 00:50:51.240 align:middle line:84%
father-child relationships, and
then friendships, and the band

00:50:51.240 --> 00:50:52.140 align:middle line:90%
altogether.

00:50:52.140 --> 00:50:54.250 align:middle line:90%
So we evolved, if you will.

00:50:54.250 --> 00:50:56.980 align:middle line:84%
We are not so much
homosapiens, right?

00:50:56.980 --> 00:50:58.230 align:middle line:90%
The clever ape.

00:50:58.230 --> 00:51:00.259 align:middle line:90%
We are homocompassionatenus.

00:51:00.259 --> 00:51:01.050 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, we are?

00:51:01.050 --> 00:51:01.760 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Exactly

00:51:01.760 --> 00:51:04.380 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And this has developed
in the last three million

00:51:04.380 --> 00:51:05.115 align:middle line:90%
years?

00:51:05.115 --> 00:51:06.626 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: I would say the
level of compassion, yeah.

00:51:06.626 --> 00:51:08.625 align:middle line:84%
Compared to like
chimpanzees or bonobos,

00:51:08.625 --> 00:51:11.480 align:middle line:84%
who are very close to us,
they're mildly compassionate.

00:51:11.480 --> 00:51:14.300 align:middle line:84%
But they're very not that
compassionate, really.

00:51:14.300 --> 00:51:18.190 align:middle line:84%
Humans are very compassionate
across all things.

00:51:18.190 --> 00:51:20.240 align:middle line:84%
So how does it help us
to be compassionate?

00:51:20.240 --> 00:51:20.740 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:51:20.740 --> 00:51:22.220 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: It's very
interesting, isn't it,

00:51:22.220 --> 00:51:24.500 align:middle line:84%
that opening your heart
to the suffering of others

00:51:24.500 --> 00:51:26.379 align:middle line:90%
helps you suffer less over time.

00:51:26.379 --> 00:51:26.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:51:26.920 --> 00:51:27.754 align:middle line:90%
That is interesting.

00:51:27.754 --> 00:51:28.920 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: It is interesting.

00:51:28.920 --> 00:51:30.770 align:middle line:84%
And you're strengthening
your own heart.

00:51:30.770 --> 00:51:33.120 align:middle line:84%
And because it's our
nature to be compassionate,

00:51:33.120 --> 00:51:36.850 align:middle line:84%
when we feel compassionate for
others, it helps us feel safer.

00:51:36.850 --> 00:51:39.860 align:middle line:84%
Because any kind of loving
feelings are a safety

00:51:39.860 --> 00:51:42.360 align:middle line:84%
signal to the ancient
lizard inside the brain.

00:51:42.360 --> 00:51:44.960 align:middle line:84%
Because as our
ancestors evolved,

00:51:44.960 --> 00:51:47.690 align:middle line:84%
exile was a death
sentence in the Serengeti.

00:51:47.690 --> 00:51:51.220 align:middle line:84%
So whether it's love flowing
in or love flowing out,

00:51:51.220 --> 00:51:53.400 align:middle line:84%
broadly defined,
it's still love.

00:51:53.400 --> 00:51:57.290 align:middle line:84%
And when you feel love for
others or loved in turn,

00:51:57.290 --> 00:51:59.140 align:middle line:90%
that says, basically, OK.

00:51:59.140 --> 00:52:01.050 align:middle line:84%
We can get out of
the red zone now.

00:52:01.050 --> 00:52:02.510 align:middle line:90%
It's safe to go green.

00:52:02.510 --> 00:52:03.820 align:middle line:90%
So that's one benefit.

00:52:03.820 --> 00:52:04.653 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:52:04.653 --> 00:52:06.870 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Also, the
compassion system,

00:52:06.870 --> 00:52:08.770 align:middle line:84%
the social engagement
system, it's called,

00:52:08.770 --> 00:52:11.625 align:middle line:84%
with related neurotransmitters
like oxytocin--

00:52:11.625 --> 00:52:12.126 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:52:12.126 --> 00:52:14.083 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: And I just want
to say for the record

00:52:14.083 --> 00:52:15.100 align:middle line:90%
guys have oxytocin, too.

00:52:15.100 --> 00:52:15.870 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, OK.

00:52:15.870 --> 00:52:18.430 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: We only have about a
seventh as much as you ladies,

00:52:18.430 --> 00:52:19.760 align:middle line:84%
but we still have
oxytocin as well.

00:52:19.760 --> 00:52:21.551 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's the chemical
that bonds women.

00:52:21.551 --> 00:52:22.795 align:middle line:90%
It's what happens when we--

00:52:22.795 --> 00:52:23.920 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: And men, as well.

00:52:23.920 --> 00:52:24.350 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --hang out together.

00:52:24.350 --> 00:52:24.850 align:middle line:90%
Oh, really?

00:52:24.850 --> 00:52:25.641 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Oh, yeah.

00:52:25.641 --> 00:52:26.420 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:52:26.420 --> 00:52:26.920 align:middle line:90%
Totally.

00:52:26.920 --> 00:52:27.110 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Good to know.

00:52:27.110 --> 00:52:30.160 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: And even in spiritual
practice, devotional practices,

00:52:30.160 --> 00:52:32.505 align:middle line:84%
of various kinds, there's
a flow of oxytocin.

00:52:32.505 --> 00:52:34.630 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Is it when we
connect with each other, or--

00:52:34.630 --> 00:52:34.885 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yes.

00:52:34.885 --> 00:52:35.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Have fun?

00:52:35.140 --> 00:52:37.390 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: I'm not trying to
reduce the mysteries of love

00:52:37.390 --> 00:52:39.515 align:middle line:84%
and friendship and going
on shopping trips together

00:52:39.515 --> 00:52:41.900 align:middle line:84%
and the delight and all that
to just one little molecule.

00:52:41.900 --> 00:52:43.260 align:middle line:84%
But it's a major
vehicle of the process.

00:52:43.260 --> 00:52:43.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's a hormone.

00:52:43.820 --> 00:52:44.445 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:52:44.445 --> 00:52:47.290 align:middle line:84%
It's a hormone outside the
brain or nervous system,

00:52:47.290 --> 00:52:48.760 align:middle line:84%
and it's called a
neurotransmitter

00:52:48.760 --> 00:52:50.468 align:middle line:84%
when it's in the brain
or nervous system.

00:52:50.468 --> 00:52:52.252 align:middle line:84%
But it's the same
molecule-- oxytocin.

00:52:52.252 --> 00:52:53.710 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And it
makes you feel good.

00:52:53.710 --> 00:52:55.572 align:middle line:90%
Is it like serotonin?

00:52:55.572 --> 00:52:57.155 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: It's
connected to serotonin.

00:52:57.155 --> 00:52:57.655 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:52:57.655 --> 00:52:59.750 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: And it helps
us bond with each other.

00:52:59.750 --> 00:53:02.310 align:middle line:84%
It helps us feel
close with each other.

00:53:02.310 --> 00:53:04.390 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes we can
go too far with it

00:53:04.390 --> 00:53:07.520 align:middle line:84%
and get very
territorial and jealous

00:53:07.520 --> 00:53:08.780 align:middle line:90%
and all the craziness of that.

00:53:08.780 --> 00:53:12.010 align:middle line:84%
But a middle amount of it,
the middle way-- right?

00:53:12.010 --> 00:53:13.620 align:middle line:90%
Moderation.

00:53:13.620 --> 00:53:17.550 align:middle line:84%
And those oxytocin systems
are connected to other systems

00:53:17.550 --> 00:53:20.030 align:middle line:84%
in the brain, like the
natural opioids that

00:53:20.030 --> 00:53:23.690 align:middle line:84%
help us feel pleasure
and joy and happiness,

00:53:23.690 --> 00:53:27.370 align:middle line:84%
including subtle forms of
just contentment and ease.

00:53:27.370 --> 00:53:28.020 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:53:28.020 --> 00:53:31.400 align:middle line:84%
So I think that, arguably, one
of the most important things

00:53:31.400 --> 00:53:34.910 align:middle line:84%
the world needs these days
and has needed all along

00:53:34.910 --> 00:53:39.030 align:middle line:84%
and will continue to need
is much more development

00:53:39.030 --> 00:53:40.730 align:middle line:90%
of practices of compassion.

00:53:40.730 --> 00:53:43.850 align:middle line:84%
It's easy and natural to
be compassionate for us.

00:53:43.850 --> 00:53:45.962 align:middle line:84%
The art is to be
compassionate for them.

00:53:45.962 --> 00:53:48.170 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's one of the
Dalai Lama's main messages.

00:53:48.170 --> 00:53:48.880 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:53:48.880 --> 00:53:51.005 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: It could be the
them who's sitting across

00:53:51.005 --> 00:53:52.540 align:middle line:84%
from you at a
dinner table, or it

00:53:52.540 --> 00:53:54.760 align:middle line:84%
could be a them down
the hall in your office,

00:53:54.760 --> 00:53:57.280 align:middle line:84%
or it could be a them on the
other side of the world, who

00:53:57.280 --> 00:53:59.571 align:middle line:84%
has a different religion from
you, a different language

00:53:59.571 --> 00:54:01.100 align:middle line:90%
from you, and so forth.

00:54:01.100 --> 00:54:03.890 align:middle line:84%
To expand compassion
while realizing

00:54:03.890 --> 00:54:05.802 align:middle line:84%
that you don't
waive your rights.

00:54:05.802 --> 00:54:07.510 align:middle line:84%
You're not agreeing
with the other person

00:54:07.510 --> 00:54:08.280 align:middle line:84%
necessarily or
approving of them.

00:54:08.280 --> 00:54:08.540 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:54:08.540 --> 00:54:09.490 align:middle line:90%
That's important.

00:54:09.490 --> 00:54:12.160 align:middle line:84%
So compassion for someone
who you don't agree with.

00:54:12.160 --> 00:54:12.785 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:54:12.785 --> 00:54:14.243 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You just
feel compassionate

00:54:14.243 --> 00:54:15.166 align:middle line:90%
for their situation.

00:54:15.166 --> 00:54:15.790 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:54:15.790 --> 00:54:17.414 align:middle line:84%
And there are different
levels of that.

00:54:17.414 --> 00:54:19.610 align:middle line:84%
One level-- I admit it--
is, you know, honestly,

00:54:19.610 --> 00:54:20.990 align:middle line:84%
if you weren't
suffering so much,

00:54:20.990 --> 00:54:22.360 align:middle line:90%
you wouldn't be such a jerk.

00:54:22.360 --> 00:54:23.260 align:middle line:90%
I mean, OK.

00:54:23.260 --> 00:54:24.715 align:middle line:90%
There's a place for that.

00:54:24.715 --> 00:54:26.870 align:middle line:84%
I mean, there are deeper,
wiser levels, too,

00:54:26.870 --> 00:54:27.921 align:middle line:90%
of just pure benevolence.

00:54:27.921 --> 00:54:28.420 align:middle line:90%
Like, wow.

00:54:28.420 --> 00:54:29.336 align:middle line:90%
I feel your suffering.

00:54:29.336 --> 00:54:30.380 align:middle line:90%
I feel your pain.

00:54:30.380 --> 00:54:34.250 align:middle line:84%
I think in the Dalai Lama's line
he says, "my friends, the enemy

00:54:34.250 --> 00:54:35.726 align:middle line:90%
Chinese government."

00:54:35.726 --> 00:54:36.350 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh wow.

00:54:36.350 --> 00:54:37.880 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Isn't that
profound and powerful?

00:54:37.880 --> 00:54:38.120 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:54:38.120 --> 00:54:39.578 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: It doesn't
mean we agree.

00:54:39.578 --> 00:54:41.390 align:middle line:84%
We maybe adversaries
at one level.

00:54:41.390 --> 00:54:45.480 align:middle line:84%
And simultaneously, I know
you don't want to die, either;

00:54:45.480 --> 00:54:47.390 align:middle line:84%
you don't want your
children to die.

00:54:47.390 --> 00:54:50.520 align:middle line:84%
I know that you, too, will face
old age, disease, and death.

00:54:50.520 --> 00:54:53.099 align:middle line:84%
And I can have that
feeling for you.

00:54:53.099 --> 00:54:54.640 align:middle line:84%
Even if I can't do
anything about it,

00:54:54.640 --> 00:54:57.800 align:middle line:84%
compassion is sincere-- even
if you can't help others.

00:54:57.800 --> 00:54:59.230 align:middle line:84%
We can have
compassion for people

00:54:59.230 --> 00:55:01.390 align:middle line:84%
on the other side of the
world or close to home.

00:55:01.390 --> 00:55:03.730 align:middle line:84%
We can't do anything
about it, but we still

00:55:03.730 --> 00:55:06.440 align:middle line:84%
wish, sincerely,
that they not suffer.

00:55:06.440 --> 00:55:08.380 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Would the ultimate
place of compassion

00:55:08.380 --> 00:55:12.837 align:middle line:84%
be for those who have killed
others or harmed others?

00:55:12.837 --> 00:55:13.420 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yes.

00:55:13.420 --> 00:55:16.070 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes,
honestly, the compassion

00:55:16.070 --> 00:55:17.940 align:middle line:84%
is not yet
authentically available.

00:55:17.940 --> 00:55:18.440 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:55:18.440 --> 00:55:19.481 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It takes a while.

00:55:19.481 --> 00:55:21.940 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: You need to go
through the cycle first of anger

00:55:21.940 --> 00:55:24.440 align:middle line:84%
or bringing to justice,
things like that.

00:55:24.440 --> 00:55:28.240 align:middle line:84%
But along the way, and then
growing over time, yeah.

00:55:28.240 --> 00:55:30.380 align:middle line:90%
I think a mature person--

00:55:30.380 --> 00:55:30.922 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:55:30.922 --> 00:55:32.421 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: --and I
don't mean an age.

00:55:32.421 --> 00:55:34.060 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I've known
eight-year-olds

00:55:34.060 --> 00:55:34.920 align:middle line:90%
who could do this.

00:55:34.920 --> 00:55:35.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:55:35.140 --> 00:55:36.931 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Where they
could have their heart

00:55:36.931 --> 00:55:39.680 align:middle line:84%
open to the kids who
were bullying them

00:55:39.680 --> 00:55:43.110 align:middle line:84%
while simultaneously really
developing strategies

00:55:43.110 --> 00:55:45.209 align:middle line:90%
to make that bullying stop.

00:55:45.209 --> 00:55:47.750 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Rather than-- that's a
better choice than victimhood.

00:55:47.750 --> 00:55:48.080 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:55:48.080 --> 00:55:48.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:55:48.470 --> 00:55:49.320 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: And it
doesn't mean that they

00:55:49.320 --> 00:55:50.640 align:middle line:90%
go to war with the bullies.

00:55:50.640 --> 00:55:50.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:55:50.960 --> 00:55:52.335 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Oftentimes
they realize

00:55:52.335 --> 00:55:56.560 align:middle line:84%
that if they get caught up with
the ones who have wronged us.

00:55:56.560 --> 00:55:57.570 align:middle line:90%
Then we're trapped.

00:55:57.570 --> 00:55:58.500 align:middle line:90%
We're stuck to them.

00:55:58.500 --> 00:55:58.912 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: The cycle.

00:55:58.912 --> 00:55:59.280 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, that's true.

00:55:59.280 --> 00:56:01.350 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: And again, compassion
is very helpful there.

00:56:01.350 --> 00:56:02.725 align:middle line:84%
You know, in a
funny kind of way,

00:56:02.725 --> 00:56:06.010 align:middle line:84%
compassion has helped me be
more skillfully assertive.

00:56:06.010 --> 00:56:07.340 align:middle line:90%
It's helped me disengage.

00:56:07.340 --> 00:56:10.180 align:middle line:84%
If I can have
compassion for you,

00:56:10.180 --> 00:56:12.147 align:middle line:84%
I can disengage from
my overreactions.

00:56:12.147 --> 00:56:13.480 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You're not as triggered.

00:56:13.480 --> 00:56:13.540 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:56:13.540 --> 00:56:14.430 align:middle line:90%
I'm not as triggered.

00:56:14.430 --> 00:56:15.090 align:middle line:90%
Exactly.

00:56:15.090 --> 00:56:16.880 align:middle line:84%
I can act more
skillfully, including

00:56:16.880 --> 00:56:18.490 align:middle line:84%
asserting myself
more skillfully.

00:56:18.490 --> 00:56:19.900 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That is a great way.

00:56:19.900 --> 00:56:20.800 align:middle line:84%
Because one of the
questions I had

00:56:20.800 --> 00:56:22.680 align:middle line:84%
was how do you turn
off being triggered

00:56:22.680 --> 00:56:24.750 align:middle line:90%
by other people's behaviors.

00:56:24.750 --> 00:56:27.520 align:middle line:84%
And that, having
compassion for them,

00:56:27.520 --> 00:56:29.430 align:middle line:90%
is a brilliant way to do that.

00:56:29.430 --> 00:56:30.060 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:56:30.060 --> 00:56:32.040 align:middle line:84%
I'll tell you two things
that are key for me.

00:56:32.040 --> 00:56:35.130 align:middle line:84%
One is, after riding
out the storm-- which

00:56:35.130 --> 00:56:37.430 align:middle line:84%
could be a few seconds
or a few hours or days--

00:56:37.430 --> 00:56:38.947 align:middle line:84%
they're like, wow,
what happened?

00:56:38.947 --> 00:56:39.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:56:39.530 --> 00:56:39.750 align:middle line:90%
And you get that shock.

00:56:39.750 --> 00:56:40.240 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: That was intense.

00:56:40.240 --> 00:56:41.330 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:56:41.330 --> 00:56:42.980 align:middle line:90%
Or, you know, like, what?

00:56:42.980 --> 00:56:43.630 align:middle line:90%
How dare you?

00:56:43.630 --> 00:56:45.620 align:middle line:84%
And you kind of sort
through what was actual

00:56:45.620 --> 00:56:48.464 align:middle line:84%
and what was overstated in your
reaction to the other person.

00:56:48.464 --> 00:56:49.130 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Made up.

00:56:49.130 --> 00:56:51.280 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: But I'm
gonna say, yeah.

00:56:51.280 --> 00:56:53.180 align:middle line:90%
They did wrong you, for real.

00:56:53.180 --> 00:56:56.210 align:middle line:84%
I find for myself if I
get to two places, that's

00:56:56.210 --> 00:56:58.240 align:middle line:90%
what gets me free.

00:56:58.240 --> 00:57:01.390 align:middle line:84%
Number one, I take maximum
reasonable personal

00:57:01.390 --> 00:57:04.770 align:middle line:84%
responsibility for
my part-- reasonable.

00:57:04.770 --> 00:57:05.320 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:57:05.320 --> 00:57:06.100 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Maximum.

00:57:06.100 --> 00:57:07.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:57:07.140 --> 00:57:08.560 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: What did I do?

00:57:08.560 --> 00:57:11.380 align:middle line:84%
What could I have
done more skillfully?

00:57:11.380 --> 00:57:13.030 align:middle line:84%
What could I learn
from this situation?

00:57:13.030 --> 00:57:13.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:57:13.530 --> 00:57:15.404 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: And then
second, I have compassion.

00:57:15.404 --> 00:57:18.110 align:middle line:84%
I find compassion for the
other person's suffering.

00:57:18.110 --> 00:57:19.990 align:middle line:90%
And isn't that interesting?

00:57:19.990 --> 00:57:23.680 align:middle line:84%
We think that if we take
responsibility for our part,

00:57:23.680 --> 00:57:26.216 align:middle line:84%
even though they did us wrong,
and if we have compassion

00:57:26.216 --> 00:57:27.590 align:middle line:84%
for them, somehow
that'll make us

00:57:27.590 --> 00:57:30.075 align:middle line:90%
a chump, a doormat, a weak link.

00:57:30.075 --> 00:57:30.700 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: No, I--

00:57:30.700 --> 00:57:31.790 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: But actually
it's the opposite.

00:57:31.790 --> 00:57:33.190 align:middle line:90%
It makes us stronger.

00:57:33.190 --> 00:57:34.215 align:middle line:90%
It makes us freer.

00:57:34.215 --> 00:57:36.090 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: In the way you're
describing it, yes.

00:57:36.090 --> 00:57:36.714 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:57:36.714 --> 00:57:38.880 align:middle line:84%
And it brings us home
to our own green zone

00:57:38.880 --> 00:57:41.280 align:middle line:90%
and unconditional inner piece.

00:57:41.280 --> 00:57:44.080 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And especially it
is such a better option

00:57:44.080 --> 00:57:46.670 align:middle line:84%
than fear, anger, and
resentment, and victimhood.

00:57:46.670 --> 00:57:47.310 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:57:47.310 --> 00:57:52.010 align:middle line:84%
And in situations-- If you go
reactive with the other person,

00:57:52.010 --> 00:57:55.312 align:middle line:84%
you start sputtering and
fuming and drama, drama, drama.

00:57:55.312 --> 00:57:57.020 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And saying
really harmful things.

00:57:57.020 --> 00:57:57.660 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Guess what?

00:57:57.660 --> 00:57:58.530 align:middle line:90%
You lose your vote.

00:57:58.530 --> 00:57:59.580 align:middle line:90%
You lose credibility.

00:57:59.580 --> 00:58:00.630 align:middle line:90%
You lose traction.

00:58:00.630 --> 00:58:03.100 align:middle line:84%
Or they overreact and
you get in these cycles.

00:58:03.100 --> 00:58:05.130 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And that brain
cascades, goes into the--

00:58:05.130 --> 00:58:05.480 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Yeah.

00:58:05.480 --> 00:58:07.620 align:middle line:84%
And the brain overlearns
with that negativity bias

00:58:07.620 --> 00:58:09.470 align:middle line:90%
from that whole business.

00:58:09.470 --> 00:58:12.580 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, if
you find your own center,

00:58:12.580 --> 00:58:17.010 align:middle line:84%
if you see more clearly,
you have compassion

00:58:17.010 --> 00:58:19.440 align:middle line:84%
for the other person,
you speak and act

00:58:19.440 --> 00:58:21.651 align:middle line:90%
in a more measured way--

00:58:21.651 --> 00:58:22.150 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:58:22.150 --> 00:58:26.120 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: --a real way, you're
much more likely to prevail.

00:58:26.120 --> 00:58:28.335 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So you slow
down your speech.

00:58:28.335 --> 00:58:29.960 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: That helps--
a little detail.

00:58:29.960 --> 00:58:31.585 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So that they
could listen, or--

00:58:31.585 --> 00:58:33.940 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Yeah, and
also, you feel centered.

00:58:33.940 --> 00:58:37.604 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Does it slow
down your rage response--

00:58:37.604 --> 00:58:39.770 align:middle line:84%
when you're really, you
know, when somebody's really

00:58:39.770 --> 00:58:40.180 align:middle line:90%
doing something wrong?

00:58:40.180 --> 00:58:41.260 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: It does
help to slow down.

00:58:41.260 --> 00:58:43.002 align:middle line:84%
I mean, Grandma's advice
is right-- you know, count

00:58:43.002 --> 00:58:43.627 align:middle line:90%
to 10, sweetie.

00:58:43.627 --> 00:58:46.543 align:middle line:84%
You know, it's good advice
for anybody at any age.

00:58:46.543 --> 00:58:47.376 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:58:47.376 --> 00:58:47.730 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:58:47.730 --> 00:58:48.938 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: That's really true.

00:58:48.938 --> 00:58:51.250 align:middle line:84%
And to be clear, I'm
not talking about a kind

00:58:51.250 --> 00:58:54.470 align:middle line:84%
of persona, which can
be really annoying.

00:58:54.470 --> 00:58:57.470 align:middle line:84%
Like, people have done therapy
and they come home, and, yes.

00:58:57.470 --> 00:58:58.764 align:middle line:90%
[MONOTONE VOICE] I hear you.

00:58:58.764 --> 00:59:00.180 align:middle line:84%
You just want to
like, whack them.

00:59:00.180 --> 00:59:02.388 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I'm talking about
something that's authentic.

00:59:02.388 --> 00:59:07.030 align:middle line:84%
But I do notice a big
difference between rolling over

00:59:07.030 --> 00:59:07.859 align:middle line:90%
and just, pssh.

00:59:07.859 --> 00:59:08.400 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right

00:59:08.400 --> 00:59:10.726 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Being nailed, or
victimized, if you will,

00:59:10.726 --> 00:59:13.469 align:middle line:84%
by the other person, or,
bam, bam, bam, going to war.

00:59:13.469 --> 00:59:14.760 align:middle line:90%
I think there's a middle place.

00:59:14.760 --> 00:59:17.657 align:middle line:84%
And you see it in great people
in the world-- Nelson Mandela.

00:59:17.657 --> 00:59:18.490 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, you do.

00:59:18.490 --> 00:59:20.970 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Aung San
Suu Kyi in Burma.

00:59:20.970 --> 00:59:22.980 align:middle line:84%
Dr. Martin Luther King,
Jr.-- people like that.

00:59:22.980 --> 00:59:24.350 align:middle line:90%
The Dalai Lama, as well.

00:59:24.350 --> 00:59:25.330 align:middle line:90%
They're centered.

00:59:25.330 --> 00:59:26.410 align:middle line:90%
They're strong.

00:59:26.410 --> 00:59:27.946 align:middle line:90%
They're the real deal.

00:59:27.946 --> 00:59:28.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: As are you.

00:59:28.920 --> 00:59:29.930 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: Oh, thank
you very much.

00:59:29.930 --> 00:59:30.930 align:middle line:84%
There's a gravity
to them, you know?

00:59:30.930 --> 00:59:31.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:59:31.690 --> 00:59:33.500 align:middle line:84%
>>HANSON: When it's
time to do that bit,

00:59:33.500 --> 00:59:34.960 align:middle line:90%
there's a gravity to them.

00:59:34.960 --> 00:59:37.430 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, thank you for
explaining that so clearly,

00:59:37.430 --> 00:59:39.590 align:middle line:84%
and for being the
example, really truly,

00:59:39.590 --> 00:59:40.840 align:middle line:90%
of what you talk about.

00:59:40.840 --> 00:59:42.548 align:middle line:84%
Even though you might
have those moments,

00:59:42.548 --> 00:59:44.620 align:middle line:84%
you really have a clear
way of explaining it

00:59:44.620 --> 00:59:46.916 align:middle line:84%
on a neuroscientific
level, psychological level,

00:59:46.916 --> 00:59:48.040 align:middle line:90%
and bringing in the Buddha.

00:59:48.040 --> 00:59:48.582 align:middle line:90%
>>HANSON: Ah.

00:59:48.582 --> 00:59:49.081 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:59:49.081 --> 00:59:50.190 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Thank you so much.

